1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 (3. Nc3 {is the most common move order} Nf6 4. d4)
3... exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 {We reach the starting
position of the Four Knights Scotch. This line always has the reputation of a
very solid but harmless option for White. This evaluation changed in the last
ten years. White found a lot of exciting ideas to put some pressure on Black's
position. The verdict of the theory is that Black is probably objectively fine,
but needs to be very precise. I also like the variation for White because we
can choose between several possible setups and even if Black equalizes, the
arising positions remain playable. Most of the equalizing lines are pretty
forced, and Black needs to remember 20+ moves to reach the slightly worse but
defendable endgame. I can recommend this setup to all who feel good playing
calm positions and torturing the opponent for many moves.} d5 (7... O-O {
is also a possible move order} 8. O-O) 8. exd5 (8. Bd2 $1 {Is a fresh and
interesting idea which scores quite well in a few high-level games recently})
8... O-O $1 {is the best move order} (8... Qe7+ $5 9. Qe2 {the practice shows
that Black has some problems in this line}) 9. O-O cxd5 (9... Bg4 {Is a tricky
move that aims to solve Black's problems tactically. In my opinion, White has
the upper hand in this line. The engines probably equalize almost everywhere,
but Black is suffering to find all good defensive moves in a practical game.
Recently this move lost his popularity.}) 10. h3 $1 {Kramnik's invention. The
idea is to follow with Qf3 and keep both Bf4 or Bg5 options possible. The move
h3 is always useful because now White's shouldn't be worried about any Bg4
tricks. I think that this is the most serious try for White in the Four
Knights Scotch.} *

