{[%evp 0,127,18,11,20,20,36,15,15,7,7,7,7,16,3,15,15,5,20,17,55,49,61,58,82,76,
73,73,73,79,109,113,110,96,168,164,164,127,126,117,151,99,102,89,138,111,111,
93,90,90,90,85,79,42,79,72,76,76,86,86,87,84,74,89,106,100,110,112,114,102,105,
90,99,103,108,109,145,132,132,125,175,150,150,112,110,116,108,65,77,84,84,85,
94,40,81,68,70,50,68,68,70,80,80,92,100,101,108,110,110,110,110,110,110,110,
110,110,110,110,110,188,247,271,271,343,485,507,527,527,527,527]} 1. e4 {
In this game we see that exchanging queens early in the opening is not very
good for Black. White's position is always slightly more preferable. White's
structure is slightly better and he can always hope for a better endgame in
this line.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3
d5 8. exd5 Qe7+ {In the past, Black tries this to swap the queens immediately,
but the practice shows that White keeps better chances in the arises queenless
middlegames} (8... O-O {Is the best move order to reach the main line.} 9. dxc6
$2 {This is too greedy and Black has a tremendous initative after:} Bg4 10. Be2
Qe7 11. O-O Rad8 12. Bxg4 Rxd1 $17 {0-1 (37) Candela Perez,J (2345)-Mitkov,N  
(2455) Orense 1997}) 9. Qe2 Nxd5 (9... Qxe2+ {The immediate exchange also
doesn't solve the problems completely.} 10. Kxe2 {White has better pawn
structure and also his pieces are sligthly more active.} Nxd5 (10... cxd5 {
If Black undouble his pawns then White has an unplesant reply} 11. Nb5 {
forcing Black's king to stay in the centre} Kd8 12. Bf4 Re8+ 13. Kf1 Ba5 14.
Nd4 Bd7 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. Bxf5 {1-0 (45) Kryvoruchko,Y (2707)-Amin,B (2635)
Dubai 2014 The engines are quite optimistic about Black's chances, but from a
human point of view White has bishop pair and better strcture. Black didn't
hold in the game:}) 11. Nxd5 cxd5 12. Bf4 (12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14. Rd1
Rhe8+ 15. Be3 Kc6 16. c4 $1 dxc4 17. Rd4 $1 $16 {Oll,L-Beliavsky,A Manila ol
1992: 1-0 (23) Zatonskih,A (2489)-Stefanova,A (2491) Beijing 2012}) 12... c6
13. c3 Be7 14. Rhe1 Be6 15. Rac1 Kd7 16. c4 Bd6 17. Bxd6 dxc4 18. Bxc4 Bxc4+
19. Rxc4 Rhe8+ 20. Kd2 Rxe1 21. Kxe1 $14 {1/2 (29) Hou,Y (2599)-Dronavalli,H  
(2503)Istanbul 2012.}) 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. a3 Ba5 (11... Bxc3+ $6 {as a rule
here, the ruined structure is not compensating the bishop pair and White is
just better here} 12. bxc3 Be6 13. O-O $14) 12. b4 Bb6 {Black needs to keep
the bishop} (12... Bxb4 $2 13. axb4 Nxc3 14. Bb2 $16) (12... Nxc3 $2 13. bxa5
$16) 13. Bb2 a5 14. O-O Nf4 $6 (14... f6 {was mandatory} 15. Rfe1+ Kf7 16. Nxd5
cxd5 17. b5 $14) 15. Rae1+ Ne6 16. Na4 f6 17. Nxb6 cxb6 18. Re3 axb4 19. axb4
Ra2 20. Rb1 b5 21. c4 $1 {The position is almost tehnically winning and
finally Karjakin manages to convert his advantage.} Rd8 (21... Bd7) 22. cxb5
cxb5 23. Bxb5 Ba6 24. Bxa6 Rxa6 25. Kf1 Rd5 26. Ke1 Kd7 27. g3 Ra2 28. h4 h5
29. Re2 Nc7 30. Bc1 Rxe2+ 31. Kxe2 g5 32. Be3 gxh4 33. gxh4 Nb5 34. Rc1 Nd6 35.
f3 Rb5 36. Bc5 Nb7 37. Bf8 Nd8 38. Rc5 Rb8 39. Rxh5 Ne6 40. Rh7+ Kc6 41. Be7
Nf4+ 42. Ke3 Nd5+ 43. Ke4 Nxe7 44. Rxe7 Rxb4+ (44... Kd6) 45. Kf5 Rxh4 46. Re4
Rh8 47. Rd4 Kc5 48. Rd3 Ra8 49. f4 Ra4 50. Rd7 Kc6 51. Rf7 Kd6 52. Rxf6+ Ke7
53. Kg6 Ra1 54. Rf7+ Ke8 55. f5 Rg1+ 56. Kf6 Rf1 57. Ra7 Rf2 58. Ra8+ Kd7 59.
Rf8 Rh2 60. Kg7 Rg2+ 61. Kf7 Ra2 62. f6 Ra7 63. Re8 Ra6 64. Re1 {1-0 (64)
Karjakin,S (2785)-Volokitin,A (2709) Istanbul 2012} *

