{[%evp 0,63,23,30,22,20,20,20,21,8,13,13,12,12,12,11,27,27,-1,19,-3,17,3,12,-3,
-11,1,-5,25,15,15,10,9,1,-10,-10,16,-3,21,23,29,15,16,10,42,45,49,39,36,34,42,
43,56,17,27,51,44,0,0,-50,0,-94,49,50,385,390]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6
4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 d5 8. exd5 O-O 9. O-O cxd5 10. h3
Rb8 {This is one of the main replies for Black, but I don't like this move
that much, because Bf4 comes with a tempo. Black's idea is Rb4 and start
moving c and d-pawns, but I think White's play is easier} 11. Qf3 c6 12. Bf4
Bd6 13. b3 Qc7 {Black forces Bxd6, but lost valuable time.} (13... Rb4 $1 14.
Ne2 $1 {White shows the right plan: Ne2 followed by c4 and Black has some
problems to protect his weaknesses} a5 {I don't think that this is a good
decision because a4 is not exactly a threat.} (14... c5 {If Black wants to
push pawns, this was a better decision.} 15. Rad1 Bb7 16. Bg5 Re8 17. Rfe1 c4
$2 {This is just a blunder} (17... Re5 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Qxf6 gxf6 20. Ng3 $14
{it is very close to equal, but I still prefer White}) 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Qxf6
gxf6 20. Bxc4 dxc4 21. Rxd6 Rb5 22. f3 Ra5 23. a4 Rae5 24. Kf2 cxb3 25. cxb3
Re3 26. b4 $18 {1-0 (39) Stevic,H (2570)-Inarkiev,E (2668) Zagreb 2021 White
easily converts his extra pawn.}) 15. Rad1 Re8 16. c4 $1 a4 17. Bc2 (17. Nd4 $1
$16) 17... axb3 18. axb3 Rb7 19. Nd4 Bxf4 20. Qxf4 Qc7 21. Qxc7 Rxc7 22. c5 $14
{1-0 (63) Xiong,J (2709)-Kovalev,V (2637) Chess.com INT 2021}) 14. Bxd6 Qxd6
15. Rfe1 Bd7 16. Qg3 {Remember this idea, guys. The computer doesn't like it,
but I find it quite instructive. White swaps the queens of the board and
forces an endgame. The arising position is objectively equal but much easier
to play for White.} Qxg3 17. fxg3 Rfe8 18. g4 {White has many ideas: like g5,
or Na4} h5 19. g5 Nh7 20. g6 Nf6 (20... Rxe1+ {was mandatory} 21. Rxe1 Nf8) 21.
Na4 Ne4 $1 {This is a serious mistake.} 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. gxf7+ Kxf7 24. Re3 {
White's knight is much stronger than Black's light-squared bishop and this is
one type of endgame you should try to reach.} Bf5 25. Rf1 Kg6 26. Rg3+ Kf6 27.
Rc3 Kg5 28. h4+ Kg4 29. Kh2 {The mating net is ready} e3 30. g3 $4 (30. Nb2 $3
$18 {[%cal Rb2c4,Rc4e3]}) 30... Re4 (30... g5 $1 $17) 31. Rxe3 Rbe8 $4 {
It was a blitz game, so let's not criticize that much the last few moves} (
31... g5 $1 $11) 32. Nc3 {with mate to follow} *

