[Source "ChessPublishing"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 O-O
8. O-O d5 9. exd5 cxd5 10. h3 {This is Kramnik's invention that brings new
life to this line. The idea is to prepare Qf3 without worrying about Bg4. In
the meantime, White is delaying the development of his dark-squared bishop. In
many cases, instead of "g5", White puts the bishop on f4, hoping to exchange
the dark-squared bishops.} Re8 11. Qf3 c6 12. Bf4 Bd7 $6 {Facing this
surprising idea, Aronian went wrong.} 13. a3 Bxc3 $6 ({better was to preserve
the bishop} 13... Bf8) 14. bxc3 Ne4 {as we already mentioned. The weakened
structure rarely compensates the bishop pair. White is already better.} 15.
Rfe1 $14 Qf6 $6 (15... Nxc3 {was the best chance} 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Qxc3 $14 {
even with opposite-colored bishops the position is far from equal with all
major pieces on the board.}) 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Qe3 $1 {again we see an example
of how the opposite-colored bishops favour White in this line. The f4-bishop
is more active than his colleague. This type of position is very unpleasant to
defend. White will try to activate his major pieces and to combine attacks
against Black's weaknesses with a kingside attack.} (17. Rxe4 $2 {allows a
nice tactic} Bxh3 $3 18. Rxe8+ Rxe8 19. gxh3 g5) 17... Be6 18. Rad1 Qf5 (18...
Bd5 19. Rd4 Qe6 20. Rb1 $16) 19. Rd4 f6 20. Rb1 $1 {Because of the f4-bishop
Black can't oppose with Rb8} (20. Rxe4 $6 {nobody cares about the pawns. Here
Black manages to exchange several major pieces after:} Bf7) 20... Bd5 21. c4
Bf7 22. Rb7 (22. Rd6 $5 Qc8 23. c5 {[%cal Rb1b4,Rb4d4,Rb1d1]}) 22... Rad8 23.
Bd6 $2 {this move loses a big part of the advantage} (23. Rxd8 $1 {was the
better move order} Rxd8 24. Bd6 $1 Bxc4 (24... Rxd6 25. Rb8+ Be8 26. Rxe8+ Kf7
27. Rxe4 $16) 25. Qxa7) 23... Rd7 24. Rxd7 Qxd7 25. Bc5 Qb7 {Black manages to
coordinate his pieces and to defend all his weaknesses. Aronian easily holds
it.} 26. Rxe4 Rxe4 27. Qxe4 Qb1+ 28. Kh2 Qb8+ 29. g3 Qa8 30. Bd6 Qe8 31. Qxe8+
Bxe8 32. Kg2 Bg6 33. Kf3 Bxc2 34. Ke3 Kf7 35. Kd4 Ke6 36. Kc5 Bd3 37. Bb8 a6
38. h4 h5 39. Kxc6 Bxc4 40. Kc5 Bb5 *

