1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bb4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Bd3 {
[%cal Bf1d3,Bd3e4,Be4c6]} d5 8. Bd2 {This is an interesting new idea that was
successfully tried in recent years by many strong players. White is not in a
hurry to change the structure with exd5, and offers a pawn sacrifice. Practice
shows that even though the arising positions are very close to equal, Black
needs to be precise. I recommend you to check all games of Sergey Karjakin
here.} O-O 9. O-O Bxc3 (9... Re8 {Is a neutral developing move} 10. Re1 (10.
Nxd5 {is also possible} Nxd5 11. exd5 Bxd2 12. Qxd2 cxd5 13. Rfe1 $14) 10...
Rb8 11. a3 Bd6 12. h3 Rxb2 {accepting the sacrifice is quite risky} 13. exd5
cxd5 14. Nb5 Ne4 15. Nxd6 Qxd6 (15... cxd6 {is better, but White keeps better
chances after:} 16. Be3 $14) 16. Bb4 (16. f3 $1 Nf6 17. Bb4 Qb6+ 18. Kh2 $16)
16... Qf6 17. Qf3 Bf5 18. Bxe4 dxe4 19. Bc3 Qc6 $4 (19... Rbb8 $11) 20. Qg3 {
1-0 (20) Kryvoruchko,Y (2699)-Banusz,T (2631) Tornelo INT 2021}) (9... a5 10.
Re1 Bg4 $1 {it is good to provoke f3 or Qc1} (10... Be6 $6 11. a3 $1 Bc5 12. h3
$1) 11. Qc1 (11. f3 Bh5 12. a3 Bc5+ 13. Kh1 Re8 $11) 11... Re8 12. a3 Bxc3 13.
Bxc3 Nxe4 $6 (13... dxe4 $1 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Bxe4 {looks ugly for Black, but
it is holdable}) 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Qf4 Bh5 16. Rxe4 $14 {1/2-1/2  (31) Erdos,V
(2615)-Mamedyarov,S (2765) Terme Catez SLO 2021}) (9... Rb8 10. Re1 Bg4 11. Qc1
Re8 12. exd5 (12. h3 Bh5 13. exd5 Rxe1+ 14. Qxe1 cxd5 15. a3 Bf8 16. b4 c5 17.
Bf4 {1-0 (73) Karjakin,S (2754)-Fridman,D (2616) Moscow 2019}) 12... Rxe1+ $1 (
12... cxd5 13. Rxe8+ $1 Qxe8 14. Bg5 $14) 13. Qxe1 cxd5 14. h3 Be6 15. b3 c5 $5
16. Na4 Bxd2 17. Qxd2 Qc7 18. Qe3 Nd7 19. Rd1 h6 20. c3 $11 {1-0 (47) Lagarde,
M (2647)-Esipenko,A (2713) Terme Catez SLO 2021}) 10. Bxc3 dxe4 (10... Nxe4 {
accepting the pawn sacrifice gives White the initative after:} 11. Bxe4 dxe4
12. Qh5 {White has a simple plan. Te1-e3-g3 with a strong attack, additionally
the e4 and c7-pawns are weak.} Qd6 (12... f5 {the engines suggests this move,
but now the White's darksquared bishop looks just too strong.} 13. f3 $1 $14)
13. Rfe1 Re8 14. Re3 Re6 $2 (14... Qd5 {looks like the better chance to hold}
15. Qh4 Bf5) 15. Rd1 Qe7 16. Rg3 Rg6 17. Qe5 Be6 18. Rxg6 fxg6 19. Qxe4 $18 {
now it is already lost. White has more active pieces and much better structure.
Karjakin won a model game, so I will leave it until the end.} Re8 20. Qxc6 Bg4
21. Qc4+ Qe6 22. Qxc7 Qf7 23. Qxf7+ Kxf7 24. Rd5 Bf5 25. f3 Bxc2 26. Ra5 Re7
27. Bd4 Bd3 28. Rxa7 Rxa7 29. Bxa7 g5 30. Kf2 Ke6 31. Ke3 Bf1 32. g3 h5 33. Kd4
Be2 34. Kc5 Bxf3 35. a4 Kd7 36. a5 Kc7 37. b4 h4 38. b5 Be2 39. Bb6+ Kc8 40. a6
Kd7 41. Ba5 h3 42. g4 Kc8 43. Be1 Kb8 44. Kb6 Bxg4 45. Bg3+ Ka8 46. Ka5 Bc8 47.
b6 g4 48. Be5 g5 49. Bd6 g3 50. Bxg3 g4 51. Bf4 g3 52. b7+ {1-0 (52) Karjakin,
S (2750)-Aronian,L (2765) Saint Louis 2019}) 11. Bxf6 {This move leads to a
slightly better endgame for White almost by force.} (11. Bc4 {is an
adventurous try, White has some compensation for the sacrificing material, but
probably not more than that.}) 11... Qxf6 12. Bxe4 Qxb2 13. Bxc6 Rb8 14. Rb1
Qxb1 15. Qxb1 Rxb1 16. Rxb1 $11 {[%mdl 4096]} Rd8 17. Bf3 Kf8 18. Rb8 Re8 {
[%cal Re8e1]} 19. h4 Ba6 20. Rb3 {two important games reached this position
and Black already shows what is the best defensive plan. It is to swap the
bishops through Be2 even with a pawn cost.} Re5 $146 (20... Re1+ 21. Kh2 Re5 {
stopping Bd5} 22. Rc3 Be2 23. Bxe2 Rxe2 24. Kg3 Re4 25. Rxc7 Ra4 $11 {1/2-1/2 
(31) Mastrovasilis,D (2619) -Grischuk,A (2773) Terme Catez 2021}) (20... Be2
21. Bxe2 (21. Bd5 $5) 21... Rxe2 22. Rc3 Re7 23. f3 Ke8 24. Kf2 {½-½ (52) So,
W (2765)-Carlsen,M (2872) Wijk aan Zee 2020 Magnus suffered a bit but drew the
game}) 21. Rc3 {This symmetrical endgame is a common theme in this variation.
With White's more active pieces, defending such a position is not easy for
Black.} Re7 22. Ra3 Re6 23. Bd5 Rb6 24. Bb3 {great maneuver. Now White's
bishop defends both c and a-pawns, and White is ready to start attacking
Black's weaknesses} c5 25. Ra4 g6 26. f3 $14 Rd6 27. c4 Ke7 28. Ra5 Kd8 (28...
Rc6 $1 29. Ba4 Rb6 30. Rxc5 Rb4 31. Ra5 Bxc4 32. Rxa7+ Kf6 33. a3 $16 {Black
has decent chances to hold this, but of course, it will be a lot of suffering.}
) 29. Rxc5 $16 {Now is just winning. All White's pawns are protected, he has a
clear extra pawn and the rest is a matter of technique. Sergey won in style
after:} Bc8 30. Kf2 Rd2+ 31. Kg3 h6 32. h5 $1 Rd6 33. hxg6 fxg6 34. Kf4 g5+ 35.
Ke5 Re6+ 36. Kd4 Re2 37. g4 Rd2+ 38. Ke3 Rd6 39. Ra5 (39. Bc2 $18) 39... Re6+
40. Kd4 Rf6 41. Bd1 a6 42. Be2 Rf4+ $2 (42... Bb7 {was the last chance} 43. Rf5
Rd6+ 44. Ke3 $16) 43. Ke3 $18 Bb7 44. Rf5 {Forcing a winning bishop ending}
Rxf5 45. gxf5 Ke7 46. c5 {[%cal Bc4c5,Bc5c6,Bc6c7][%mdl 32]} Kf6 47. Bd3 Ke5 (
47... a5 48. f4 g4) 48. Be4 Bc8 49. c6 h5 50. c7 a5 51. a4 Kf6 52. Kf2 h4 53.
Kg2 Ke5 54. Kh2 Kf6 55. Bd3 Ke5 (55... Bb7 $18 56. Be4 Bc8) 56. Bf1 Kf6 57. Bh3
Bd7 58. Bg4 Bc8 59. Kg2 Bd7 60. Kf2 Bc8 61. Ke3 Bd7 62. Kd4 Bc8 63. Kc5 Kf7 64.
Kb6 *

