1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {This is known as the Schmidt
Variation.} 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 {The main point of exchanging the knight on c6
is to push this central pawn to e5 to disturb the knight on f6.} Nd5 {Without
the inclusion of 6...Qe7 7.Qe2 the direct 6... Nd5 is dubious as our bishop on
f1 is not blocked by the queen on e2.} (6... Ne4 7. Nd2 {Challenging the
e4-knight and in turn developing our pieces with tempo.} Nxd2 (7... Nc5 8. Nb3
{Chasing the knight also paves a way for our c1-bishop. Next on the agenda is
Be3.} Qe7 9. f4 g6 10. Be3 Nxb3 11. axb3 {The a-file is also opened now for
the rook on a1.}) 8. Bxd2 d5 (8... d6 {This is simply bad in view of} 9. Qf3)
9. Bd3 {Idea is to 0-0 next and go for f4} Qh4 {Black's idea is to prevent f4
idea with Bc5} 10. Be3 {0-0 can be played but this is simply much better
according to the engines.} (10. O-O Bc5 11. Qe1 O-O 12. Be3 $14) 10... Qb4+ {
What else? otherwise white just runs away with 0-0 and f4} 11. c3 Qxb2 12. O-O
{[%eval 32764,0] Followed by f4, White has simply menacing compensation here.})
7. c4 Nb6 (7... Bb4+ {Rarely played but still it's good to consider forcing
moves.} 8. Bd2 Bxd2+ 9. Qxd2 Nb6 10. Nc3 Qe7 11. O-O-O $14) 8. Be3 {Not the
main move but once again top choice of the engines.} (8. Bd3 {Can be tried as
well} d6 (8... g6 9. h4) 9. exd6 Bxd6 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 Be6 12. b3 {with a
typical structural advantage.}) 8... d6 {Black would eventually have to break
the centre.} (8... g6 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. c5 {[%csl Gb6]}) 9. exd6 Bxd6 (9... cxd6
10. Bd3 d5 {This is the only way to challenge white's centre.} 11. O-O Be6 (
11... Be7 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Qc2 h6 14. Rfe1 {[%cal Ga1d1] with the typical idea
to play against black's centre.}) 12. Nd2 dxc4 13. Be4 Qc7 14. Qf3 Rc8 15. Bd4
{Not letting black develop his kingside, which gives us ample compensation for
the pawn.}) 10. c5 Be5 11. Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. Nc3 Nd5 13. O-O-O {White is of
course better with his two bishops.} *

