1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 f6 {A natural move trying to break the centre immediately.} 9. c4 {
Disturbing the knight which is dominating on d5.} Ba6 {A standard development
of the bishop that makes use of our placement of our queen on e2 and now Black
can maintain his knight on d5 for a while.} (9... Nb6 10. exf6 {Exploiting the
drawback of the knight retreating back to b6 from d5. Now the pawn structure
of Black is simply weakened as Black is forced to capture the pawn on f6 with
his g7-pawn.} Qxe2+ (10... gxf6 11. Nc3 Ba6 12. b3 d5 {Otherwise white enjoys
a free edge.} 13. Rh3 {Threatening Re3. So, Black is forced to take on e2.} (
13. Bb2) 13... Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2 O-O-O (14... dxc4 15. Re3+ Kd8 (15... Kf7 16.
Bh5+) 16. Bb2 Kc8 17. Re6 $16) 15. cxd5 Bxe2 16. Kxe2 cxd5 17. Kf1 $14 {
[%cal Gc1b2,Gh3f3,Ga1d1] And once again, the defective pawn structure of Black
gives White a slightly better position.}) 11. Bxe2 gxf6 12. Nc3 {Thanks to the
worse pawn structure of Black, White is clearly better here.}) 10. Rh3 {
The point of h4} fxe5 (10... Nb6 11. exf6 {The standard reaction when the
Knight retreats to b6. The standard reaction when the knight retreats to b6.}
Qxe2+ 12. Bxe2 Bxc4 {Otherwise white would simply have a better structure for
free.} 13. Re3+ Kd8 {Only precise move.} (13... Be6 14. Bg4 Nd5 15. fxg7 Bxg7
16. Re2 O-O 17. Bxe6+ {And White has a microscopic edge thanks to the weakened
pawn islands of Black. Play might continue} dxe6 18. Na3 {Only square for the
knight as 18.Nd2 allows 18...Nf4} Rab8 {Exerting pressure on the b2-pawn.
Thanks to the activity, Black is very close to achieving equality despite the
scattered pawn structure.} 19. Kf1 {White secures his king with the idea of
g3-Kg2 next.} Rb4 {Attacking the h4-pawn.} 20. g3 {[%eval 32764,0] Next on the
agenda is Kg2 followed by Nc2-Ne3 and White has some pressure. This is the
best practical try and the maximum White can achieve from this line. Chapter
21: Scotch: 4...Nf6-8...f6 9.c4 Ba6}) (13... Kf7 {was played in the game
between Cheparinov-Jones 2019.} 14. fxg7 Bxg7 15. Bh5+ Kg8 16. Nc3 $40) 14.
fxg7 Bxg7 15. Nc3 Re8 16. Rxe8+ Kxe8 17. Bg5 {I still feel black has to be
very precise to make a draw here.}) 11. Bg5 Nf6 (11... Qb4+ 12. Nd2 Qxb2 13.
Rb1 Qd4 14. Rhb3 Nf4 15. Bxf4 Qxf4 16. g3 Qf5 17. Rb8+ Rxb8 18. Rxb8+ Kf7 19.
Rb3 Kg8 20. Qe3 {With multiple ideas like Qa7 and Bd3} Qc2 21. Bd3 Qc1+ 22. Ke2
$40) 12. Re3 {Black has some problems now on the e-file.} O-O-O (12... d6 13.
Qf3 {Attacking the c6-pawn and was played two times by the Scotch expert
Nepomniachtchi.} e4 {13...Bb7 is met by 14.Rb3 O-O-O 15.Nd2 and Black faces
huge problems in freeing his position.} 14. Qd1 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) 13. Ra3 {
Not an easy move to face OTB.} Bb7 {The only move} (13... Qb4+ 14. Nc3 Bxc4 (
14... Bb7 15. O-O-O Bc5 16. Rb3 Qa5 17. Bd2 $40) 15. Qxc4 Qxc4 16. Bxc4 Bxa3
17. bxa3 d5 18. Ba6+ Kd7 19. Na4 $16) 14. Nc3 d5 15. cxd5 cxd5 16. Rb3 {
With the idea of Qb5} c5 (16... c6 17. Rc1 Kb8 18. Na4 $40 {[%cal Ga4c5]}) (
16... h6 17. Qb5 c5 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Rd1 {[%cal Gc3d5]} d4 20. Bd3 {Black's
position is falling apart.}) 17. Rd1 {[%csl Gd5]} c4 18. Rb5 Qe6 19. Bxf6 gxf6
20. Rdxd5 Bxd5 21. Nxd5 Qc6 22. Qg4+ f5 23. Qxf5+ Qd7 24. g4 $44 *

