1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8.
h4 Qe6 9. Nd2 {Now black has few options here} a5 {The standard expansion with
the idea to bring the c8-bishop into play.} (9... Nb4 {Black has dual plans:
Attacking the c2-pawn and planning ...Ba6.} 10. Nf3 Ba6 11. c4 d5 12. a3 Bxc4
13. Qd1 Bxf1 (13... Na6 14. b4) 14. Kxf1 Na6 15. b4 {White is just cruising
through.}) (9... d6 {is not that great here as Black has already wasted one
move with ...Qe6 . If Black wants to break the centre, then 8...d6 is what he
needs to do.} 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Nc4 {With the idea to take on d6} Bc5 (11...
O-O 12. Qxe6 Bxe6 13. Nxd6 cxd6 14. Bd2 {Followed by long castle and White
enjoys a better position thanks to the bishop pair.}) 12. a3 {Played by
Caruana! Restricting Nb4 and Bb4} O-O 13. Qxe6 Bxe6 14. Bd3 {White should be
slightly better because of his pawn structure.}) 10. g3 {Activating our own
light-squared bishop to the other route as our queen is hindering it in the
f1-a6 diagonal. Now the bishop will either land on g2 or h3 depending on the
situation.} Nb4 (10... f6 11. c4 Nb6 (11... Nb4 {is not that great as after}
12. Nf3 {White prevents Nc2+ and he gets a3 next. a3 would kick the knight and
force it to go back to a6 where it remains passive.} Bc5 13. Bh3 {Intermediate
move before kicking the knight.} Qe7 14. a3 {Now the knight is forced to go to
the rim.} Na6 15. exf6 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 $14) 12. exf6 d5 13. cxd5 cxd5 {So Black
sacrifices his pawn to free his position with the f8-bishop going to g7, but
instead we maintain the tension by} 14. Nb3 {Forcing Black to take on f6 which
will again leave him with a defective pawn structure.} gxf6 15. Bd2 {With the
idea to play Nd4 next, white is slightly better here.}) (10... Ba6 11. c4 Nb6 (
11... Nb4 $2 12. Bh3 f5 13. O-O $16) 12. b3 Bb4 13. Bh3 {Once again, thanks to
the pawn on g3, White chips in with Bh3 to gain a tempo by disturbing the
queen. White also completes his development before Black opens up with ...d5.}
Qe7 14. O-O d5 15. Bb2 {Now that white has stabilised the centre he should be
slightly better here.}) 11. Nf3 Ba6 12. c4 Qg6 {with the idea of Nc2} (12... c5
$2 13. Ng5 Qc6 14. Rh2 $16 {Threatening Bg2.}) 13. Kd1 {White loses the right
to castle, but preventing Nc2+ is important. Moreover, Black will not be able
to exploit our king position as he has problems with his development and White
is in the driver's seat of creating threats. White at least has two moves like
a3 and h5 at the moment to create play.} (13. h5 Qc2 14. Rh4 c5 15. a3 Qxe2+
16. Kxe2 Nc6 17. h6 Rb8 18. Rb1) 13... c5 {Now that Black has provoked Kd1, he
can afford to play ...c5 to secure a square for his b4-knight after a3. This
tends to be dubious without the inclusion of Qg6 and Kd1.} (13... h5 $6 14. a3
Nd5 15. Ng5 Nb6 16. b3 $14 {[%cal Ge2f3,Gf1d3]}) 14. a3 {Played only once, can
be a massive surprise.} (14. h5 Qb6) 14... Nc6 15. h5 Qe6 16. Bf4 $146 Be7 17.
Rc1 O-O $6 {This has very subtle refutation.} (17... O-O-O 18. Bh3 f5 19. Re1
$36 {[%cal Gc1c3,Gd1c1]}) 18. h6 g6 19. Bh3 f5 20. exf6 Qxf6 21. Re1 Rad8 22.
Rc3 {Surprisingly black is completely lost here.} *

