Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. h4 {This has been the trend recently.} a5 {
Black wants to play Ba6 next and usually, it's a good idea to expand with a5}
9. c4 Nb6 {One of the two options for black to react after c4} (9... Ba6 10.
Nd2 {Here the problem with 10.b3 is that Black has 10...g6 with the idea of
Bg7 and pressurize the e5-pawn. 11.Bg5 Qb4+ 12. Bd2 Qe7 and White has nothing
more than a draw. So instead of 10.b3, White plans to develop his pieces
quickly by 10.Nd2.} (10. b3 g6 11. h5 Bg7 12. f4 O-O) 10... f6 (10... Nb6 11.
b3 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gc1b2]} g6 12. Bb2 Bg7 13. h5 {h6 is coming next.} O-O (
13... O-O-O 14. h6 Bf8 15. O-O-O $16) 14. f4 d6 15. O-O-O {We can also start
with g4} dxe5 16. g4 {With the idea to go f5 next.} a4 17. f5 $36) (10... Nb4 {
This just helps white.} 11. Nf3) 11. g3 {The point is that if the direct 11.b3
Nf4 is incoming and Black will be able to take the e5-pawn with his queen as
his knight is no longer hanging on d5. Hence we play 11.g3 to prevent ...Nf4
jumps.} fxe5 12. b3 O-O-O 13. Bg2 (13. Ne4 Nf6 14. Bh3 h6 15. O-O g5 $1 $40)
13... Nf6 (13... e4 14. Nxe4 Nf6 15. Nxf6 Qxf6 16. Bb2 Bb4+ 17. Kf1 Bc3 18.
Bxc3 Qxc3 19. Rd1 $14 {[%cal Gf1g1,Gg1h2]}) 14. O-O {With Bb2 and Nf3 coming
next, white is simply much better.}) 10. h5 {A rare move, just played four
times. It gives us more flexibility to as h5 has to be played anyways in this
line. We can later decide the fate of our b1 knight.} Qe6 (10... Ba6 11. b3
O-O-O {11...a4 will be met by 12.Bb2 as well.} 12. Bb2 {And here there are two
plans for Black to challenge the e5 pawn: either by ...d6 or ...f6.} f6 (12...
d6 13. exd6 Qxe2+ 14. Bxe2 cxd6 15. Bc3 $16) 13. Nd2 fxe5 14. O-O-O Re8 15. Re1
$44 {[%csl Ga6,Gb6]}) 11. Be3 {Now you can see why committing Nd2 early on
move 10 is not that great as without it, we can develop our dark-squared
bishop. Moreover, the advantage of placing the bishop on e3 is that we are
targeting the b6-knight and can exchange any time when the c4-pawn needs
defending. And if 11.h6 here Black has an intermezzo with 11...Bb4+ followed
by ...g6.} Qxe5 {Grabbing the central pawn looks obvious, but in return opens
up the e-file and White rushes to castle long after} (11... Bb4+ 12. Nd2 Ba6
13. Rh4 $1 {The point of h5} Bxd2+ 14. Kxd2 $1 O-O-O 15. Qg4 $14 Qxe5 $2 16.
Bd4 Qe6 17. b3) 12. Nd2 Be7 13. O-O-O {Next the knight is headed to f3 to
disturb the queen on e5.} Bf6 14. Nf3 Qe7 15. Qc2 O-O (15... d6 16. Re1 $44 {
[%cal Gf3d4]}) 16. g4 $40 *

