[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4...Qh4"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C45"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "21"]
[EventDate "2022.02.04"]
[Source "ChessPublishing"]

{[%evp 0,21,24,41,30,44,44,33,4,11,9,23,26,32,20,20,20,20,20,20,20,3,8,49]} 1.
e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {Let's have a look at the most relevant
sidelines to avoid any unpleasant surprises!} Qh4 {This is a move that is very
often played by club players. Quite obviously, in our computer era, such
exotic moves simply do not work. By sacrificing a pawn, White is getting a
very powerful initiative. Since our play is pretty straightforward, you don't
need to learn the theory by heart.} 5. Nc3 $1 Bb4 {This is the only way to
justify the early queen sortie. Black just wants to win the e4-pawn. The
entire concept, however, turns out time-consuming.} ({After} 5... Bc5 6. Be3
$16 {It's not clear what the queen is doing on h4. White will simply proceed
with Be2 followed by 0-0. One needs to understand that White is statically
better since the e4-pawn provides a space advantage in the centre. Therefore,
Black is the one who should play very energetically.}) 6. Be2 $1 {The most
precise continuation. White sacrifices the e4-pawn in order to quickly develop
his pieces.} Qxe4 ({After} 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qxe4 8. Nb5 Kd8 {we transpose to
the main line.} ({Note that} 8... Qe5 {loses on the spot in view of} 9. f4 {
[%csl Rc7] when the black queen can no longer safeguard the c7-pawn.})) ({
A recent online blitz game saw} 6... Nxd4 $2 {which is pointless since after}
7. Qxd4 {Black cannot oppose White's powerful centralized queen. After} Bxc3+
8. Qxc3 {[%cal Gc3c7,Gc3g7]} Nf6 9. Qe5+ Kf8 10. Bg5 d6 11. Qxf6 {Black
resigned in the game 1-0 (11) Nabaty, T (2638)-Williams, S (2464) Chess.com
INT 2021}) 7. Ndb5 $1 {Remember this key move. Now, the black king will be
forever stuck in the centre.} Bxc3+ ({Black can also start with} 7... Kd8 {
After} 8. O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 {we just transpose to the main line.}) 8. bxc3 Kd8
9. O-O {[%csl Gc1,Gc2,Gc3,Bd8,Ge2][%cal Gc1a3] This is the critical position
for the evaluation of Black's concept. It's important to understand the nature
of White's advantage. Black's biggest problem is the permanent vulnerability
of his king. Therefore, even if you do not play in the most precise way, Black
will experience problems. Additionally, White enjoys a tremendous advantage in
the development and powerful bishop pair. When we speak about the bishop pair,
our doubled pawns are an advantage since the c1-bishop gets access to the
a3-square. In general, doubled pawns are often useful in the fight for an
initiative since they provide open files and diagonals for our pieces.
Basically, this is all that you should know about the move 4...Qh4. I could
have stopped my analysis here, claiming a big advantage for White.
Nevertheless, I decided to provide some examples. Memorizing them is
completely useless. Just try to spot some recurrent motifs.} Nf6 ({After} 9...
d6 $2 {besides all other moves, we can play} 10. Nxd6 $1 {within a second. The
king is helpless since all White pieces are participating in the attack.} cxd6
11. Qxd6+ Ke8 {[%csl Be8]} 12. Bf3 Qe6 13. Qc7 Nge7 14. Ba3 {[%cal Ba1f1,Bf1e1]
After connecting the rooks, White is ready to proceed with Rfe1. The game is
pretty much over. After} Qd7 15. Qg3 Nf5 16. Qf4 Nce7 17. Rfe1 h5 18. Rad1 Qb5
19. Qg5 Be6 20. Bxe7 f6 21. Bxf6 Kf7 22. Bxg7 {Black resigned in the game 1-0
Smeets-Pliester, Netherlands 2003.}) ({Another high-level game saw} 9... a6 10.
Bf3 Qg6 11. Nd4 {when it's not clear how Black will develop his pieces. White
is completely winning.} Ne5 ({Even worse is} 11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 {[%cal Bc1f4,
Bf1e1,Ba1d1,Bc3c4,Bc4c5] White has a crushing advantage. After developing the
bishop on f4, White will put his rooks in the center. Whenever Black plays ...
d7-d6, the advance c3-c4-c5 comes on the agenda.}) 12. Bh5 Qf6 13. Re1 d6 {
This position has been reached in the game Ponkratov, P - Sevian, S, lichess.
org INT 2020. At this point, the most precise would have been} 14. c4 Bd7 15.
c5 $18 {with a winning attack. A possible follow up would be} dxc5 16. Nb3 {
[%cal Gb3c5,Gd1d5]} b6 17. Qd5 {[%csl Ra8,Re5][%cal Gd5e5,Gd5a8]} Nc6 18. Bg5
$18) 10. Re1 ({Another option is} 10. Rb1 a6 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. cxd4 Re8 13. Bf3
Qg6 14. Bf4 $44 {with good compensation for the pawn in Van der Wiel-Pliester,
Enschede 2003.}) 10... Re8 11. Bg5 {[%cal Ge2f3,Gd1d2,Ge1e8,Ga1e1] White has a
big advantage. His next moves are Qd2 and Bf3. Black has problems developing
his pieces.} *

