against Cheparinov.} a6 14. Kh1 $16 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gb4b5] White is simply better
since it's not clear how Black will handle the idea of Nc4 followed by b4-b5.})
12. Nbd2 Ng6 13. Bg3 O-O 14. a4 {White is ready to start the expansion. The
following moves seem pretty logical -} a5 15. Nc4 axb4 16. cxb4 Nf4 17. Nxb6
cxb6 18. Bb5 Bg4 {This position was reached in the game Anish Giri - Dmitry
Andreikin, Tata Steel - A 79th Wijk aan Zee, 2022. At this point, White's most
promising option would have been} 19. h3 Bh5 20. Kh2 {Black does not have
compensation for his terrible pawn structure and White's strong bishop pair.
It's important to mention that} f5 {can be answered with} 21. Qb3+ Kh8 22. exf5
Rxf5 23. Bxc6 bxc6 24. Nd4 $16 {with a big advantage.} *

