{[%evp 0,37,34,20,24,24,24,9,9,9,34,34,34,19,19,6,83,89,85,87,74,73,90,95,101,
101,85,87,139,64,93,64,126,95,106,78,78,74,61,67]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4
exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3 Be7 {A system with a solid reputation, although the
ensuing positions are looking passive for Black.} 6. Nf5 Bf6 {White should
already reckon with the advance ...d7-d5 after which the f5-knight will be
vulnerable. Therefore, the most logical continuation is} 7. Ne3 {As we have
seen on multiple occasions, the control of the d5-square is very important in
this pawn structure. Meanwhile, White has now the opportunity to start
expanding on the kingside by means of f2-f4.} g6 {[%cal Gf6g7,Gg8f6] This is
Black's most ambitious idea. He is planning to proceed with ...Bg7 followed by
...Nf6, thus putting pressure on e4 and supporting the advance ...d7-d5. The
drawback of this concept is that the d5-square is now vacant for the white
knight.} ({The alternative} 7... Nge7 {is too passive. Since there is no
pressure on e4, White can play} 8. f4 Ng6 {The knight is not well placed on g6
since White can restrict it's mobility by means of the simple g2-g3.} ({
It's important to consider} 8... d6 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O g6 {[%cal Bf6g7,Bf7f5,
Bc8e6,Bd8d7] The computer gives White a considerable advantage in this
position. Such an evaluation is meaningless if you don't know how to handle
the structure. Black is planning to proceed with ...Bg7, ... Be6, and ...Qd7
followed by ...f7-f5. Therefore, in my opinion, White should opt for the
thematic} 11. f5 $1 {[%csl Bf5,Bc8,Be7,Bf1][%cal Be3g4,Bd1d3,Bd3h3] Gaining
space on the kingside is far more important than the e5-square. Behind the
f5-pawn, White can build a strong attack. A typical idea is Ng4 followed by
the manoeuvre Qd3-h3.} Ne5 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] planning to exchange the
e5-knight by means of Ndc4.} gxf5 ({After} 12... Bd7 {White can develop his
attack in a typical way -} 13. Ndc4 Kh8 ({Note that} 13... N7c6 {allows} 14.
Nd5) 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Qd3 $40 {[%cal Ge3g4,Gd3h3] with Ng4 and Qh3 to follow.
White has a dangerous attack.}) 13. exf5 Bg5 14. Ndc4 Kh8 15. f6 N7g6 16. Nd5
$16 {White's advantage is obvious.}) 9. g3 {[%csl Gf4,Gg3,Bg6,Gh2] The pawn
chain h2-g3-f4 significantly reduces the activity of the black knight.} h5 10.
Bg2 h4 {This position was reached in the game 1-0 (22) Colmenares, A (2368)
-Jenni, F (2469) Zuerich 2017. Now, the simplest would have been} 11. Na3 d6
12. Qe2 $18 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge1c1] followed by Bd2 and 0-0-0. White has a winning
advantage since Black has no counterplay at all.}) 8. Nd5 $1 {This is the move
that puts Black entire strategy under suspicion.} ({The point behind Black's
setup was very well illustrated in the following game:} 8. Bc4 d6 9. O-O Bg7
10. f4 Nf6 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Bd3 Re8 $132 {The vulnerability of the e4-pawn
gives Black sufficient counterplay. 0-1 (38) Sheng,J (2411)-Ipatov,A (2650)
Philadelphia 2018}) 8... Bg7 9. Na3 $1 {[%cal Ga3b5] Once again, the
vulnerability of the c7-pawn is becoming Black's Achilles heel in the Scotch.
The threat is Nb5 on the next move.} a6 {The only defence.} ({After} 9... Nce7
$2 10. Nxc7+ $3 Qxc7 11. Nb5 Qe5 12. Nd6+ Kf8 13. Be3 $44 {[%csl Bf8][%cal
Bd1d2,Be1c1,Bf1c4] White enjoys a tremendous compensation for the piece.}) ({
After} 9... Nf6 $2 10. Bg5 {[%cal Gh4d8] Black has no good way to get rid of
the pin.} h6 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Rc7] The c7-pawn is again a big
problem.} Be5 13. f4 a6 14. Qa4 Rb8 15. fxe5 axb5 16. Bxb5 O-O 17. O-O $18 {
White is winning.}) 10. Bg5 $1 {This is the point! Now, Black has nothing
better than taking the bishop -} Qxg5 $5 ({After} 10... Nce7 11. Bc4 $1 $16 h6
12. Qf3 $1 $18 {the pressure on f7 decides the game.}) ({Too ugly is} 10... f6
{when after} 11. Bh4 Nh6 12. Bc4 $18 {Black cannot finish the development.}) (
10... Nge7 {This move was played in the game 1-0 (32) Karttunen, M (2451)
-Mertanen, J (2293) Tampere 2018. At this point, instead of 11.Nf6+, White
should have played} 11. Qf3 d6 12. Bc4 Be6 13. Nf6+ Bxf6 14. Bxf6 $18 {with a
decisive advantage.}) 11. Nxc7+ Kd8 12. Nxa8 Nf6 13. Qc1 $1 {This is the most
elegant solution.} ({Nevertheless, the alternative} 13. g3 {is possible as
well. For example, after} Nxe4 14. Bg2 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Qe7+ 16. Kf1 Qxa3 17. Rb1
{[%cal Ga8b6] Black does not have compensation for the exchange.}) 13... Qc5
14. Qe3 $1 Nxe4 ({The alternative} 14... Qxe3+ 15. fxe3 b5 16. Nb6 Bb7 17. Rd1
Ne5 18. Nd5 Nxe4 19. Be2 $16 {does not give Black sufficient compensation.})
15. Be2 (15. Qxc5 Nxc5 16. Nb6 {is possible as well.}) 15... Re8 16. Qxc5 Nxc5
17. Kf1 b5 18. Nb6 Bb7 19. Rd1 $16 {Black does not have any compensation for
the exchange.} *

