{[%evp 0,41,25,25,27,27,27,30,39,26,46,32,74,85,107,10,23,21,20,13,7,10,-1,10,
10,10,17,6,14,14,25,12,12,20,27,30,40,-58,126,130,106,143,137,105]} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3 Bc5 {This is a more popular continuation
than 5...Be7. In my opinion, however, the entire system is very passive since
White obtains a lasting edge in a Maroczy Bind type of structure.} 6. Be3 Bb6 (
6... Nf6 $2 {loses a piece after} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bxc5 $18) (6... Qf6 {[%cal
Bf8b4,Bb4c5,Bg8e7,Be8g8]} 7. g3 Nge7 8. Bg2 {[%cal Bd7d5]}) 7. Nf5 $1 {Forcing
the exchange of dark-squared bishops and preparing a setup with pawns on c4
and e4 and knights on c3 and e3.} Bxe3 (7... Qf6 $6 {is a rare move and can
best be met by} 8. Na3 $1 Nge7 9. Nb5 Ba5 (9... Kd8 10. Qd2 Bxe3 11. Nxe3 $16 {
wasn't much fun for Black either in Jarmula-Chylewski, Graz 2017.}) 10. Nxe7
Qxe7 11. Bd3 d6 12. O-O O-O 13. a4 {and White is just better in
Lagno-Stefanova, Tashkent 2013. Even simplified position after} Bb6 14. Bxb6
axb6 15. f4 $16 {Black is suffering from some structural problems on the
queenside.}) (7... d5 $6 8. Nxg7+ Kf8 9. Nh5 Bxe3 10. fxe3 Qg5 11. Nf4 Bg4 (
11... dxe4 12. Nd2 Nf6 13. Be2 Bf5 {1-0 (33) Warmerdam,M (2595)-Nesterov,A  
(2514) Chess.com INT 2021} 14. Qb3 $1 $18) 12. Be2 Ne5 13. O-O dxe4 14. Bxg4
Qxg4 {1-0 (25) Hakobyan,A (2598) -Theodorou,N (2554) ICC INT 2021} 15. Qd5 $18)
8. Nxe3 {[%cal Bc3c4,Bb1c3]} Nf6 (8... d6 9. c4 (9. g3 {is possible here as
well, but then Black might still consider a more active way of developing his
knight, e.g.} Nf6 10. Bg2 O-O 11. c4 $14) 9... Nge7 (9... Nf6 10. Nc3 O-O 11.
f3 {transposes to the Main Line with 8...d6.}) 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Bd3 (11. g4 $6 {
(stopping ...f7-f5)} Ng6 12. Qd2 {was played in Zhou,-Bok, Porto Carras 2010,
but now after} Qh4 $15 {Black has a firm grip on the dark squares.}) (11. Be2
$6 {allows} f5 $1 12. exf5 Nxf5 13. Nxf5 Bxf5 $132 {with excellent play for
Black in Nepomniachtchi-Kramnik, Sochi blitz 2014.}) 11... f5 $5 (11... Kh8 {
has been played in quite a couple of games, but it seems Black can play ...
f7-f5 without this preparatory move.} 12. O-O f5 13. f4 Be6 14. Qd2 Qd7 15.
Rae1 $14 {Amonatov-Sakaev, St Petersburg 2015}) 12. exf5 Nxf5 13. Bxf5 Bxf5 {
[%csl Bc4]} 14. Qd5+ (14. O-O $5 Qd7 15. Qd2 Rae8 16. f4 Kh8 {(anyway...)} 17.
Rae1 Ne7 {as played in Tari-Johannessen, Norway 2018. Probably it's a good
moment to start expanding on the kingside with} 18. h3 $5 $14) 14... Kh8 15.
Nxf5 Qf6 (15... Nb4 16. Qd2 Rxf5 17. O-O Qd7 18. Rae1 $14 {Belikov-Yandemirov,
Alushta 2012.}) 16. O-O (16. O-O-O $5 $146 Qxf5 17. Qxf5 Rxf5 18. f3 $14 {
followed by doubling rooks on the e-file. Only White can be slightly better,
even though it might not be anything special, like in the lines with 16.0-0.})
16... Qxf5 17. Qxf5 Rxf5 18. f4 {[%csl Be5][%cal Ba1e1,Bc3d5,Bg2g3]} g6 (18...
Kg8 19. Rae1 Kf8 20. Re4 (20. g4 $5) 20... Re8 21. Rfe1 Rxe4 22. Rxe4 Nb4 $1
23. b3 d5 24. cxd5 {½-½ Nasuta-Postny, Zagreb 2017.}) 19. Rae1 Kg7 20. Nd5
Rf7 {and soon a draw had been agreed in Khairullin-Alekseev, St Petersburg
2012.}) (8... Nge7 {Since Black has committed his knight to e7, I think the
setup with} 9. g3 $5 {makes quite some sense.} (9. c4 d6 {would transpose to
positions examined with 8...d6.}) 9... d6 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O Kh8 12. Nd2 (12.
f4 {which comes down to the same after} f5 13. Nd2) 12... f5 13. f4 $1 (13.
exf5 {but I would prefer maintaining the tension for a while.}) 13... fxe4 (
13... Be6 14. exf5 (14. Qc2 $14) 14... Nxf5 15. Nxf5 Bxf5 16. Qb3 Rb8 17. Rae1
Qd7 18. Nf3 (18. Re3 $5 {looks like a simpler way for White to proceed.}) 18...
Bd3 19. Rf2 Rfe8 20. Rxe8+ Qxe8 21. Ng5 $6 (21. Qd1 $14) 21... Qe1+ 22. Bf1 h6
23. Nf3 {was seen in Vidit-Abdulla, Chengdu 2017 and now according to the
silicon monster Black could have maintained the balance with} (23. Kg2 $5)
23... Qc1 $1 $132 {In any case, from a practical point of view I wouldn't
recommend White allowing the Black queen from entering via the e-file.}) 14.
Nxe4 {[%csl Bh2,Bg3,Bf4,Bc6,Be7][%cal Bd1d2,Bf1e1,Bc3c4,Bd2c3]} Nf5 15. Re1
Nce7 (15... Nxe3 16. Rxe3 Bf5 17. Qb3 Rb8 18. Ng5 Qd7 19. Rae1 {just with
simple moves White has obtained a huge advantage. The following game nicely
shows how White should convert his positional dominance into a full point:} h6
20. Ne6 Rfe8 21. Qd5 Bxe6 22. Rxe6 Rxe6 23. Rxe6 Ne7 $2 (23... Re8 {though
after} 24. Rxe8+ Qxe8 25. Kf2 $16 {Black is awaiting a long torture.}) 24. Qe4
Ng8 25. Qf5 Rd8 26. Be4 g6 27. Qxg6 d5 28. Bd3 d4 29. Rf6 Nxf6 30. Qxf6+ Kg8
31. Bc4+ Kh7 32. Bf7 Rg8 33. Bxg8+ Kxg8 34. Qg6+ {1-0 Aryan-Rajdeep, Ahmedabad
2017.}) 16. Nxf5 (16. Ng5 {is likely to transpose.}) 16... Nxf5 17. Ng5 h6 18.
Ne6 (18. Qh5 $6 g6 19. Qxg6 hxg5 {as tried in Kovalev-Mikaelyan, Jerusalem
2015, is also worth considering but there is no need for White to enter the
complications.}) 18... Bxe6 19. Rxe6 $16 {and White is clearly better in
Matlakov-Postny, St Petersburg 2018 thanks to the control of the open e-file.})
9. f3 {[%cal Bc3c4]} (9. Bd3 $6 {should be met by} d5 $1 {not giving White a
second chance playing c3-c4.}) 9... O-O 10. c4 d6 11. Nc3 Nd7 {Other moves
have been tried here as well, but they don't change the character of the play.}
12. Be2 (12. Qd2 {possibly transposes, although in quite a number of games
White players have played this move with the intention of castling queenside.})
(12. Bd3 Nc5 13. O-O Nxd3 14. Qxd3 $14 {was played in Muzychuk, A-Korneev,
Linares 2018, but since White has a pleasant space advantage I would prefer
keeping some minor pieces on the board.}) 12... Nc5 13. O-O {[%cal Bd1d2,Bc3d5,
Bb2b4,Bf3f4,Be2f3,Ba1e1]} a5 (13... f5 $2 14. exf5 Bxf5 {was seen in Van
Kampen-Babula, Warsaw 2013 and now White could have obtained a huge advantage
by means of} 15. b4 $1 Qe8 (15... Ne6 16. f4 Ned4 17. Bh5 {and Black has
serious coordination problems, in view of threats b4-b5 and g2-g4.}) (15...
Nxb4 16. Nxf5 Rxf5 17. Qb1 $18 {is the tactical justification.}) 16. Ncd5 (16.
Nxf5 Rxf5 17. bxc5 Qe3+ 18. Kh1 Qxc3 19. cxd6 cxd6 20. Rb1 $16 {is also great
for White.}) 16... Ne6 17. f4 $16 {and White has a massive advantage.}) 14. Qd2
Be6 (14... Bd7 15. f4 Ne7 16. Bf3 Bc6 17. Rae1 {As so often in these position
Black is lacking an active plan.} Kh8 18. Nc2 Ng6 19. g3 Ne7 20. Bg2 f5 21. Nd4
Bxe4 22. Bxe4 fxe4 23. Nxe4 Nf5 24. Nxf5 Nxe4 25. Rxe4 Rxf5 26. Rfe1 {and once
again, White controls the only open file:} Qf8 27. R1e3 h6 28. g4 Rf7 29. f5
Rd7 30. Qe2 Qf6 31. Re6 Qd4 32. Kg2 d5 $2 33. Re8+ Rxe8 34. Rxe8+ Kh7 35. g5 $1
g6 36. Re7+ Rxe7 37. Qxe7+ {Idani-Gordievsky, Qinhuangdao 2018.}) (14... Ne7
15. f4 (15. Rad1 {which was played in Hommeles-Sarakauskas, Baden 2013. In the
ensuing structures where Black meets f2-f4 with ...f7-f5 the white rooks are
best placed on e1 and f1.}) 15... f5 16. Bf3 Bd7 17. Rae1 Kh8 18. exf5 Nxf5 19.
Ne4 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Nxe3 21. Rxe3 $14 {Adair-Sarakauskas, England 2018.}) (14...
f5 $2 {is premature, in view of} 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. Nxf5 Rxf5 17. f4 Kh8 18.
Rae1 $16 {Vitoux-Wantiez, Reunion 2007.}) 15. f4 {[%csl Be6][%cal Bf4f5,Bf5f6]}
f6 16. Bf3 Qe7 17. Rad1 $16 {Black's position is quite passive, but his next
move allows a beautiful breakthrough:} Qf7 $2 18. e5 $1 f5 (18... dxe5 $2 {
runs into} 19. f5 $1 {[%cal Bf3d5]} Bc8 20. Bd5 {and White wins material.}) (
18... Bxc4 $2 19. Nxc4 Qxc4 20. Bd5+ $18) (18... fxe5 19. f5 Bxf5 20. Bd5 Ne6
21. Nxf5 $18) 19. exd6 Rad8 20. Nb5 cxd6 21. Qc3 $18 {and White is winning in
Tari-Esipenko, St Petersburg rapid 2018.} *

