{[%evp 0,41,28,20,24,24,13,9,9,9,42,48,87,63,46,22,1,1,-3,-3,-3,1,-1,-11,-25,
-18,-6,5,6,8,25,24,24,41,39,39,45,74,74,77,86,36,36,114]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3 Bc5 6. Be3 Bb6 (6... Nf6 $2 {loses a piece after}
7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Bxc5 $18) ({After} 6... Qf6 {Black basically transposes to the
line with 4...Bc5 5.Be3 Qf6 with the move c2-c3 included. White's most logical
continuation is} 7. g3 Nge7 8. Bg2 {when Black is not in time to execute the
advance ...d7-d5.}) 7. Nf5 $1 {Another critical branch is Forcing the exchange
of dark-squared bishops and preparing a setup with pawns on c4 and e4 and
knights on c3 and e3.} g6 8. Bxb6 axb6 {[%cal Ba8a1]} 9. Ne3 Nf6 {[%csl Be4]
[%cal Bf2f3,Bb1d2]} 10. f3 {[%cal Bc3c4,Bb1c3]} (10. Nd2 $6 d5 $1 {is very
comfortable for Black.}) 10... O-O (10... Qe7 11. c4 Qb4+ (11... Qc5 12. Kf2
$16) 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 d6 14. Nc3 Kd8 {has been seen in numerous games.
White's edge is beyond any doubt, but Black is quite solid. I analyze this
endgame in some of the model games.}) 11. c4 {Black has to make an important
decision here. Playing slowly leads to a clearly inferior structure as White
has a nice grip on the central squares. However, the dynamical approaches  
(both 11...Nh5, intending f5 & 11... d5) aren't solving Black's problems
either.} Nh5 (11... d5 12. cxd5 Nxe4 13. fxe4 $1 Qh4+ 14. Kd2 $1 (14. Ke2 {
which was played in Oleksienko-Godena, Gjakova 2016. The white king is safer
on the queenside and on e2 it obstructs the light-squared bishop.}) 14... Qxe4
15. Bd3 $1 Qd4 (15... Qb4+ $2 {just enables White to consolidate with} 16. Nc3
Ne5 17. Qb3 $18 {and White is winning in Vovk, A-D'Amore, Gallipoli 2016.}) 16.
Qb3 $1 (16. dxc6 $6 Qxb2+ 17. Nc2 Rd8 {leads to unnecessary complications.})
16... Re8 17. Re1 (17. dxc6 $2 Rxe3 18. Re1 Rxe1 19. Kxe1 {was played in
Zierk-Grover, chess.com INT 2019 when Black has several winning continuations,
of which I consider} Bf5 $1 {as the most convincing. For instance} 20. Bxf5
Re8+ 21. Kf1 Qf4+ 22. Qf3 (22. Kg1 Re1#) 22... Qc1+ 23. Kf2 Qe1#) 17... Ne5 18.
Na3 $1 (18. Qc3 $2 Qf4 $1 19. Na3 {as played in Zumsande-Jones, Douglas 2015
and here Black could have seized the initiative by means of} Ra5 $1) 18... Nxd3
({A new GM game saw} 18... Bd7 19. Nac2 Qf4 20. Qc3 $16 {Black does not have
enough compensation for the piece. 1-0 (54) Christiansen, J (2582)-Theodorou,
N  (2577) Warsaw 2021}) 19. Nac2 $1 (19. Qxd3 Qxb2+ 20. Nac2 {as played in
Danin-Zeller, Wunsiedel 2016 also favours White, but after} Qe5 $14 {Black has
some hopes to generate counterplay.}) 19... Qf4 20. Qxd3 $18 {and White is
winning. An important detail is that} Bf5 {can be met with} 21. Rf1 Qh6 22.
Rxf5 gxf5 23. Qxf5) (11... d6 12. Nc3 Nh5 13. Qd2 Ng7 (13... Be6 14. O-O-O Ne5
15. Kb1 f5 16. exf5 gxf5 17. Ned5 c6 {was seen in Brandenburg-L'Ami, Dieren
2007 and here} 18. Nxb6 Qxb6 19. Qxd6 $18 {would have been decisive.}) 14. Bd3
Ne5 {was played in Lagno-Ovod, Chita 2015 and here I would rather go for} 15.
O-O $16 {with similar play as in other lines.}) (11... Qe7 $6 12. Nc3 Qc5 13.
Qd2 Nb4 14. Rc1 Qe5 15. a3 Nc6 16. Ncd5 Ne8 17. Bd3 d6 18. O-O $16 {and even
though Black went on to win in Rublevsky-Sokolov, Kragujevac 2009 his position
is absolutely horrible.}) 12. Qd2 f5 {The principled continuation, but with
precise play White retains a big advantage. The alternatives are simply too
passive:} (12... Na5 13. Na3 $1 (13. Nc3 $2 {in view of} Nb3 $1) 13... d6 14.
g3 $16 {with a clear edge for White in Chigaev-Gasanov, St Petersburg 2013.
White is going to follow up with Bg2 and 0-0, while Black is lacking
counterplay against pawns on c4 and d4.}) (12... Ng7 13. Bd3 d6 14. O-O f5 15.
f4 Be6 16. Nc3 Qf6 17. Rae1 Rae8 18. b3 fxe4 19. Bxe4 Nf5 {and now in
Deac-Tomazini, Budapest 2018 White could have increased his advantage with} 20.
Ned5 Qd8 21. g4 $1 {intending to bring the pawn to g5, preparing Nf6 at a
suitable moment.}) 13. exf5 $1 (13. Nc3 $6 {is less convincing, because of}
fxe4 (13... f4 $2 14. Ned5 Qh4+ $2 (14... d6 15. O-O-O) 15. Qf2 Qd8 16. Nb5 $18
{and Black is lost in Yu Yangyi-Bu Xiangzhi, Doha blitz 2016.}) 14. Nxe4 {
was played in Recio-Girones Barrios, Cocoa Beach 2017 and now after the simple}
d6 {Black obtains reasonable play.}) 13... Qh4+ (13... Re8 14. Nc3 Qh4+ {
was seen in Gusain-Sanikidze, Amol 2018 where White went for 15.g3, which is
also good, but in my opinion simpler is} 15. Kd1 $1 {with the point that after}
Ng3 16. hxg3 Qxh1 17. Kc2 $18 {compared with that game White has an extra
g-pawn.}) ({After} 13... gxf5 14. Nc3 d6 15. O-O-O f4 16. Ned5 $16 {White's
advantage was undisputable in the game 1-0 (28) Shahinyan, D (2452)-Song, M  
(2421) Chess.com INT 2020}) 14. Qf2 Qd4 15. Nc3 $1 Re8 16. Ne4 $1 Nf6 (16...
gxf5 17. Nxf5 Qxf2+ 18. Kxf2 $16 {and White has an extra pawn.}) (16... Ra3 $2
{looks spectacular but was easily refuted after} 17. Nd5 $1 Qe5 18. fxg6 Nf6
19. Qh4 Nh5 20. Qxh5 {1-0 Antal-Cruz, Barcelona 2017.}) 17. Bd3 d5 {and so far
we have been following the game Pichot-Flores, Buenos Aires 2017. Now the
simple} 18. Nxf6+ Qxf6 19. O-O {gives White a winning advantage. After} Qd4 20.
Rfe1 {Black can't play} Qxd3 {in view of} 21. Rad1 *

[Event "Chess24 Banter Blitz Cup Final"]
[Site "chess24.com INT"]
[Date "2022.02.05"]
[Round "1.6"]
[White "Jones, Gawain C B"]
[Black "Aronian, Levon"]
