{[%evp 0,94,19,31,34,25,22,20,28,11,31,50,61,60,49,31,-6,-9,-7,-9,-5,-6,3,1,36,
37,30,30,34,18,63,48,61,48,53,52,52,46,61,42,51,21,250,247,253,224,224,178,169,
158,152,152,148,152,147,149,144,155,178,178,185,197,139,145,151,164,154,150,
148,125,122,134,157,160,167,174,174,177,186,178,169,182,238,174,219,219,298,
258,319,324,379,381,397,388,402,410,405] This is a model game featuring the
Maroczy Bind structure after the exchange of the queens. It seems that Gawain
Jones found the optimal setup for his pieces. The critical position arises
after move 14...Kd8.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bb4+ 5. c3 Bc5 6.
Be3 Bb6 7. Nf5 g6 8. Bxb6 axb6 9. Ne3 Nf6 10. f3 Qe7 11. c4 Qb4+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+
13. Kxd2 d6 14. Nc3 Kd8 {[%csl Rc7,Gd5][%cal Ge3d5,Gc4d5] This is the first
critical position. Defending the c7-pawn with the king is Black's key idea in
this line. Later on, by exchanging minor pieces, Black wants to reduce the
importance of White's space advantage. On the other hand, the outpost on d5
gives White a lasting edge in this structure. Definitely, he will install a
knight on that square. Since Black cannot live for too long with such a
monster on d5, he will probably exchange it. Then, after cxd5, White will
start putting pressure against the backward c7-pawn. If Black chases the
knight away by means of ...c7-c6, then the d6-pawn becomes a weak backward
pawn. Dorfman was right when pointing out that when we have an outpost sooner
or later our opponent will end up with a backward pawn in his camp.} 15. Be2 {
[%cal Ge3d5,Gc3b5] In order to provoke the exchange on d5, White will put his
knights on d5 and b5, putting maximum pressure on c7. Besides that, gaining
space on the kingside is White's other typical idea in such positions.} h5 {
A typical move played with the idea to prevent g2-g4.} 16. Rhd1 Re8 17. Ke1 Bd7
18. Rac1 Ra5 19. a3 h4 20. Nb5 {Everything is ready for this idea. White's
next move is going to be Nd5.} Ra8 $4 {It's really difficult to explain this
decision. Now, White is winning on the spot.} ({Better would have been} 20...
Ne5 {when after} 21. Rc3 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gc4c5] White keeps only slight advantage.
He is planning to open the position by means of b2-b4 followed by c4-c5.}) 21.
Nd5 Nxd5 22. cxd5 $18 {White is already winning. Later on, Jones managed to
convert his decisive advantage.} h3 23. gxh3 Rh8 24. dxc6 bxc6 25. Nc3 Rxh3 26.
Kd2 Ke7 27. Ke3 Rxh2 28. Rh1 Rhh8 29. f4 b5 30. Bf3 Rxh1 31. Rxh1 Rb8 32. Na2
c5 33. Nc3 c6 34. Kd2 b4 35. axb4 cxb4 36. Nd1 Ra8 37. Ne3 Ra2 38. Kc2 Ra5 39.
Rh8 Be6 40. Rb8 Ra4 41. Rb7+ Kf6 42. Rb6 d5 43. exd5 cxd5 44. Bxd5 b3+ 45. Bxb3
Rd4 46. Kc3 Rd8 47. Bxe6 fxe6 48. b4 Ra8 49. Kd4 Rd8+ 50. Ke4 Rd2 51. b5 Rb2
52. Ng4+ Ke7 53. Ne5 Rb4+ 54. Kf3 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

