{Let's take a brief look at another example featuring the pressure on c7. In
this position, Rublevsky played} 27. Ned5 $1 {which is basically winning. If
Black does not exchange on d5, White's next move will be Nb5.} Nxd5 28. cxd5
Ne5 29. f4 Ng4 30. Bxg4 hxg4 ({In case of} 30... Bxg4 31. Nb5 Re7 32. Nxd6+ $18
{White is winning on the spot.}) 31. e5 {[%cal Gc3e4] Not the only move but
completely enough.} Kd8 {This is the most tenacious defence.} ({After} 31...
dxe5 32. d6 c6 33. Nd5 Ra7 34. Nc7 Rh8 35. fxe5 {Black's position is hopeless.}
) 32. Ne4 dxe5 33. Nf6 Re7 $2 {This is losing immediately.} ({Black should
have played} 33... exf4 34. Nxe8 Kxe8 35. gxf4 Kd8 {Even though White is
winning, there still can be some fight.}) 34. Rxc7 Bf5 35. Rxe7 Kxe7 36. fxe5
Rc8 37. Rf2 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

