{In the last example, I would like to make some important remarks concerning
the kingside pawn play. The position on the diagram has been reached in the
game Gawain, J - Degraeve, J, 2022. Instead of 15.Be2 that Jones played
against Aronian, this time he preferred} 15. g4 {immediately gaining space on
the kingside.} h6 16. h4 Be6 17. Be2 Nd4 18. b3 {You should never be afraid of
allowing your opponent to exchange his knight for the bishop. The e2-bishop is
the most problematic piece in our camp.} Nxe2 19. Nxe2 c6 20. Kc3 Ke7 21. a4
Nd7 22. g5 $6 {[%cal Bh8h7,Ba8h8,Bg5h6] This is a very instructive mistake.
Since gxh6 would damage White's pawn structure, now Black is the one who will
decide when to release the kingside tension.} ({The right way of gaining space
in such structures is} 22. h5 {[%cal Ge2f4] White is going to follow with Nf4,
putting additional pressure on g6. The idea is to provoke Black to play either
...g6-g5 (weakening the f5-square) or ...gxh5 which creates many weaknesses.}
Nf6 23. Nf4 g5 24. Ne2 $16 {Now, the knight is ready to manoeuvre all the way
to f5 with a huge advantage.}) {At this point, Black could have played} 22...
Rh7 $1 {[%cal Ga8h8] preparing to double the rooks on the h-file. After ...
hxg5, Black will be ready to invade via the h-file. That's why the advance
g4-g5 was premature.} ({The game saw} 22... hxg5 {I leave the game text
without comments.} 23. hxg5 Nc5 24. Nd4 Bd7 25. b4 Rxh1 26. Rxh1 Nxa4+ 27. Kb3
b5 28. cxb5 Nb6 29. bxc6 bxc6 30. Rc1 Rc8 31. Kc3 c5 32. bxc5 Rxc5+ 33. Kd2
Rxg5 34. Rb1 Nc8 35. Nd5+ Kd8 36. Ke3 Be6 37. Nf4 Bd7 38. Rh1 Nb6 39. Rh7 Be8
40. Nde6+ fxe6 41. Nxe6+ Kc8 42. Nxg5 {1-0 Black resigns.}) 1-0

