1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {In my view, the move 4...Nf6 here for
Black is very slightly better than 4...Bc5 but I would say that 4...Bc5 is
easier to learn.} Bc5 {Out of all the moves for White here, the most practical
one is clearly} 5. Nb3 {White's idea, generally, is to castle long and attack
Black's king. Of course, Black has various set-ups, and he even has the
possibility to castle long. We will examine all of this in this lecture.} Bb6 {
Yes, there is a line starting with 5...Bb4+ but after 6.c3 or even 6.Bd2,
White seems to have a nice advantage. Now, there are several move-orders like
6.Qe2 or 6.Nc3 first. In fact, they look a lot like each other and quite often,
these two moves will transpose.} 6. Qe2 {First, we will begin with the most
important part of the lecture right from the start which is when Black is left
without pawn breaks. What are Black's possible pawn breaks here objectively?
The pawn break with d5 and the pawn break with f5 mainly. We will see there is
a third one sometimes. What happens if Black is not able to carry out any of
these breaks? Then out of nowhere, White will get a huge advantage.} d6 $6 {
This move, surprisingly, appears to be already inaccurate. Black should be
very fast with his counterplay either starting with Nge7 and a fast f5 or
playing Nf6 here and constantly threatening d5. However, most players, just
like here Jakovenko with a rating of 2736, without really thinking about it,
will play a move like d6. What is the problem with this move? It is very slow.
Now White should play Nc3, exchange dark-squared bishops and castle long. Is
Black already worse by force here? I would say "slightly worse". But if he
continues with d6 and Nf6, he may end up "much worse", in fact, because he is
deprived of any pawn break.} 7. Be3 {Generally, it is a very important
principle in these types of positions that it is very good for White to
exchange dark-squared bishops. If White, all of a sudden, exchanges and then
Black, surprisingly, is left without counterplay.} Nf6 8. Nc3 Be6 (8... Bxe3 9.
Qxe3 O-O 10. O-O-O {Already such a position is much better for White. Not just
slightly better but much better because Black is left without pawn play. None
of the pawn advances like a5 or d5 are possible or effective.} Re8 ({Let's
suppose he goes here} 10... a5 {in various lines. Do you need to know the
concrete theory? Absolutely not. That's a good thing about this position.
There are a couple of possible reactions here for White.} 11. Nd4 {Whenever
you see this move a5 and we are able to play Nd4, you should automatically
execute this move and now White is clearly better. This a5 move now appears to
be totally pointless.} ({And even better possibility than 11.a4 would be} 11.
a3 {ruling out any a4-a3 ideas for Black.}) ({Another possible reaction would
be} 11. Bb5 {we are ready to capture a4 whenever he plays it.}) ({Sometimes
even} 11. a4 {is possible. This move does have some drawbacks, of course. This
a4-pawn is what we call a hook but, nevertheless, it is not so easy for Black
to open up the position with b5. White even here is better. But we are really
not forced, at this moment, to play a4.}) {For example,} 11... a4 (11... Re8 {
Let's strengthen our centre with} 12. f3 Bd7 {Many moves are available for
White.} ({How about} 12... Nxd4 {I would say this is slightly better than
allowing Ndb5 but again after} 13. Qxd4 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] it is
quite clear that this a5 is totally random. The b5-square is available for our
knight and for our bishop. There is absolutely no attack by Black while White
has very simple plans. He will start pushing g4, h4, h5, g5 and gain a huge
initiative.} Be6 14. g4 Nd7 {You don't need to know absolutely any theory.
White is enjoying a huge advantage.} 15. h4 {is playable.} (15. Be2 {is
playable. More generally, I prefer to develop pieces. For example,} Qf6 {
we can even trade queens and in this endgame, White is still clearly better.}
16. Qxf6 ({Of course, we can also withdraw the queen by such a move} 16. Qd2 {
[%cal Gg4g5,Gh2h4] intending to simply continue with g5 and h4.}) 16... Nxf6
17. g5 Nd7 18. Nb5 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] It is very difficult now for
Black to chase our knight away while we will keep on gaining space with h4-h5,
f4 leading to a more or less winning endgame for White.})) {He can play} 13. g4
{[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Yg4g5] intending h4-h5 and maybe later g5.} ({He can even
play} 13. Ndb5 {This is a very typical move now that Black played a5. Putting
pressure on the d6-point because the move c6 is never available because d6
will always be dropping and White is already enjoying a huge advantage.
Believe me when you are playing these lines with Nb3, quite often even strong
opponents with a rating of over 2300 will not know what to do with Black. They
will play a fast d6 and end up in a position just like this one without any
pawn breaks which is strategically and tactically lost.})) {we will play} 12.
a3 {for theoretical and for practical reasons.} ({For example, let's imagine I
play such a move} 12. Be2 {and he will definitely go} a3 {and} 13. b3 {
Although the computer will show that White is still better here, nevertheless,
with this annoying pawn on a3, Black even in totally lost positions will have
some counter chances. So we better stop this pawn with 12.a3.})) 11. f3 {
Black is already much worse. There is really nothing much he can do. There is
no} d5 (11... Be6 {White will immediately continue with} 12. g4 {This is an
important move because, at any moment, we want to be able to play g5 and chase
away the knight from the centre. And when this knight is away from the centre
then there is no pawn break with d5. White is already much better. Any
computer will confirm that immediately.} Bxb3 {Should I be careful with this
capture? Absolutely not.} (12... a5) {I can take with the a-pawn.} 13. axb3 ({
But even better and a more standard move is} 13. cxb3 {[%cal Gc1b1] Now our
king sooner or later will go to b1.} Nd7 {I would prefer to play it safe with}
14. Kb1 {[%cal Gf1c4] Again, it is very obvious that Black doesn't really have
a plan and we will start advancing the pawns. If you ask your computer, it may
tell you in such a position +2 already for White because it calculates many
moves ahead and it sees that Black has absolutely no plan and we keep on
pushing our pawns. Additionally, our bishop can find a nice outpost on c4 at a
good moment - maybe not immediately.})) {We just move our queen} 12. Qf2 {
[%csl Rd5] and this pawn will soon drop due to tactics.}) 9. O-O-O O-O {
[%cal Gf2f3,Gg2g4,Gh2h4,Ge3b6] There is nothing tremendous that White needs to
do here. He will simply start advancing his pawns with f3, g4, and h4. At a
good moment, he may even capture on b6, surprisingly. This move taking on b6,
initially, appears to be very strange at first because it opens Black's rook.
However, White still has very good chances after taking on b6 at the right
moment because some squares have been weakened and, as we will see, White can
take advantage of it.} 10. f3 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4]} Re8 ({Let's say, Black tries
to be clever with} 10... Bc4 {I will tell you that such gain of tempi in such
positions is totally harmless. In fact, they are pretty mistaken. White can
continue with} 11. Qf2 Bxe3+ 12. Qxe3 Bxf1 13. Rhxf1 {[%cal Gg2g4] and is much
better already. The next move is going to be g4. But when I see} a5 {I don't
need to play 14.a4 but the typical reaction once again would be} 14. Nd4 Ne5
15. g4 {A general principle we mentioned is that} Nc4 {such gain of tempo are,
surprisingly, completely wrong and completely pointless.}) ({Let's suppose he
would go} 10... Ne5 {I would have played} 11. Kb1 {This move is more or less
necessary. Are exchanges generally good for White? Generally, we would like to
exchange dark-squared bishops and this is for sure going to happen. Other than
that, we can exchange some pieces - that is not bad. But we should not
exchange every piece because otherwise, our attack will be powerless.} Bxe3 12.
Qxe3 {For example, here I don't, all of a sudden, want to play a move like Nd5
and exchange more pieces because I need to use his Nf6 in order to gain tempi
for my attack.} Nc4 {Once again, totally harmless.} 13. Qf2 ({We can even play
such a move} 13. Qe1) ({Even} 13. Qg1 {if I ask my computer who is better
here? The computer will say that White is much better even after this horrible
Qg1 move.}) ({A very typical idea is} 13. Bxc4 {If I have to say which pieces
to exchange, generally, some exchanges to avoid all complications are good.
Generally, I like to take a knight on c4 because} Bxc4 {Black's bishop is
actually very bad. Here, theoretically speaking,} 14. Nd4 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gg2g4,
Gh2h4] would have been the best intending g4 and h4. Once again, Black doesn't
really know what to do.} ({However, even} 14. g4 Bxb3 {I prefer to take with
the c-pawn.} 15. cxb3 {Yes, we have exchanged some pieces - but not every
piece. There are still enough pieces to give him checkmate. To make, as they
say, a long story short: We love to exchange dark-squared bishops, this is
very important; and it is going to happen. At some moment we may even capture
on b6. And we may exchange one more pair of pieces. But definitely, we should
keep at least some minor pieces, at least a pair of knights.}))) 11. Bxb6 $3 {
This is really a great move. This is what Carlsen has always been doing when
playing in such structures.} (11. g4 $16 Ne5 12. h3 Bc4 13. Qf2 Bxf1 14. Rhxf1
$16) 11... axb6 {Why is he doing that? First of all:} 12. Qd2 $16 {This is a
very basic move. Be careful about the move Qd2. What is this move doing?
Several things: It is restoring the coordination of our pieces. Now our bishop
is ready to be developed. For the moment, we played Qe2. Why did we play that?
Because we wanted to play Be3. There is no other way to exchange dark-squared
bishops. Only with Qe2 and Be3 - no other way Be3 could have been avaílable.
The b5-square is a hole now (for our bishop) and with Qd2 we also prevent his
d5 advance.} Nd7 {Jakovenko decided he is never going to break with d5.} (12...
Na5 {I would have played} 13. Nd4 ({Other moves are also possible. After} 13.
Kb1 {again, White is much better. If} Nc4 ({And if he takes on b3} 13... Nxb3
14. cxb3 {[%cal Gg2g4] and then g4 is coming. Look, Black does have an open
file but not really something concrete.} Qe7 15. g4 Ra5 {Doubling rooks here
appears to be a waste of time.} 16. g5 Nd7 17. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5] White has much
more clear threats. He wants to play f5 and develop his pieces. There is not
much Black can do. In fact, the positional mistakes have been made previously.
Black is deprived of pawn play.}) {I would possibly take it.} 14. Bxc4) 13...
Nc4 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 15. a3 $16 (15. b3 $1 Be6 16. Kb2 Qe7 17. a4 $18 Red8 18.
Rhe1 Nd7 19. g4 $18) 15... Nd7 16. g4) (12... Qe7 {13.Kb1 is interesting but
not really necessary because if he takes on b3, we intend to take with the
c-pawn anyway.} 13. g4 {White, again, has a huge advantage.} (13. Bb5 {[%cal
Gg2g4] This is a possible move, just pinning the knight and the next move,
again, is g4.}) 13... Nd7 14. Kb1 {We can play 14.Bb5, maybe even 14.h4.} Nc5
15. Bb5 $14 {You don't really need to know much. In all of these types of
positions, White is clearly better.}) 13. Bb5 $1 {Carlsen always likes to put
his bishop here.} Nc5 (13... Na7 {would have been an interesting possibility.
After} 14. Be2 ({I would say a simpler solution is} 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 {At this
moment, maybe I would like to play} 15. Kb1 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gh2h4] and then we
start with g4 and h4. How about} f5 {because I have said that so far Black
doesn't have any pawn breaks. Yes, this came a bit too late and is totally
meaningless this pawn break now.} 16. exf5 Bxf5 17. g4 Be6 18. Nd4 {and again
White has a very nice advantage in the centre.}) {Black wants to play} 14... b5
{maybe, some small tactic in order to start pushing pawns because the a2-pawn
is hanging.}) (13... Bxb3 14. cxb3 Nf6 15. Kb1 $18) 14. Nd4 $16 {is what
Carlsen likes to play.} Bd7 15. Kb1 Nxd4 16. Qxd4 Bxb5 17. Nxb5 {Again, here
White has an advantage. Not such a big one though. In the end, though, in the
complications, Black managed to win but that does not really mean anything
about the opening.} Qd7 18. c4 Ra4 19. Rhe1 Ne6 20. Qc3 Qc6 21. b3 Ra5 22. a4
$16 Raa8 23. Rd5 h6 24. g3 Red8 25. h4 Qe8 26. Rdd1 Qe7 27. Nd4 Nxd4 28. Rxd4
Qe6 29. g4 Qf6 30. h5 Re8 31. Kb2 Re6 32. Rd5 Qh4 33. Re2 Rae8 34. Qe1 Qf6+ 35.
Qc3 Qh4 36. Qe1 Qh3 37. Rd3 c6 38. Red2 d5 39. cxd5 cxd5 40. e5 Rxe5 41. Qd1
Re1 42. Qc2 Qg3 43. Qc3 Rf1 44. Rc2 Qf4 45. Rxd5 Rxf3 46. Qd4 Qg3 47. Rd8 Rxb3+
48. Ka2 Ra3+ 49. Kb2 Qb3+ 50. Kc1 Rxd8 51. Qxd8+ Kh7 52. Qc8 Ra1+ 53. Kd2 Qd5+
54. Kc3 Qe5+ 55. Kb3 Rb1+ 56. Kc4 Qe4+ 57. Kc3 Qb4+ 58. Kd3 Rd1+ 59. Ke3 Qd4+
60. Kf3 Qd3+ 61. Kg2 Qf1+ 62. Kg3 Rd3+ 63. Kh2 Rh3# 0-1

