1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 {Carlsen usually prefers}
6. Qe2 ({You will see many of the games start with} 6. Nc3 {which is similar
to Qe2.} d6 {Again, another slow move. But we need to exchange dark-squared
bishops. But how to do that?} 7. Qe2 ({If it was possible theoretically, we
would like to play} 7. Be3 {which, of course, is not possible because he will
take it.} Nf6 8. Qd2 {Now White would have an even better version of this game
because he put his queen on d2 immediately in one move. But unfortunately,
this is not possible and otherwise, there would be no 4...Bc5 at all for Black.
})) 6... d6 $6 {Again, this slow move. A very typical mistake.} ({Now this} 
6... a5 {is an interesting possibility and White needs to play} 7. a4 ({
Okay, this} 7. Be3 {is also maybe playable but 7.a4 is a better move.} a4 8.
N3d2 (8. Bxb6 axb3 9. Be3 Rxa2) 8... Bxe3 9. Qxe3 Nf6 10. Bd3 O-O 11. O-O d5)
7... d6 8. Nc3 $6 (8. Be3 $3 Bxe3 9. Qxe3 Nb4 (9... Nf6 10. Nc3 Nb4 11. O-O-O
O-O 12. f3 $16) 10. Qd2 $1 Nf6 11. Nc3 Qe7 12. O-O-O O-O (12... Be6 13. Nd4)
13. f3 $14) 8... Nb4 $1 $36) 7. Be3 (7. Nc3 $1 {This is a bit more accurate
but Be3 is almost the same.} Nf6 (7... Nge7 8. Be3) 8. Be3) 7... Nf6 {7...Nge7
would have been better as we will see later. Again, this d6 is too slow.} ({
Now the computer suggests} 7... Qf6 $5 {this set-up which we will examine a
bit later. Again, White is slightly better but perhaps his advantage is a bit
reduced. After 7. Nc3 we rule out this possibility.} 8. Nc3 Nge7) 8. Nc3 O-O 9.
O-O-O {White is, again, clearly better.} Re8 10. f3 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Ye3b6,
Ye2d2] The next move is going to be g4 or even Bxb6 and Qd2.} Be6 11. Bxb6 axb6
12. Qd2 Bxb3 13. cxb3 $18 {Again, White is much better. White knows very well
- because he has studied these types of positions - that the a-file, no matter
if Black takes on b3 or if he doesn't take, cannot cause any damage.} Qe7 {
14.Kb1 can be played but I don't think it is really necessary.} 14. Bb5 $1 {
Now Black cannot move his knight from f6 because Nd5 is coming. He cannot move
his knight from c6 because the rook drops. First, he needs to move his rook
from e8 but who would play Red8 in this position? So, in fact, Black is facing
a tough choice.} Qe5 15. Kb1 $1 {Just to protect against Rxa2 sacrifices.
Carlsen, generally, likes to have everything protected.} Red8 16. a3 {is also
possible to prevent any Nb4 ideas.} ({Yes, there are other possibilities as
well. The computer, for example, says that} 16. f4 {is completely winning for
White.}) 16... Ne7 (16... Na7 17. Be2 c6 18. g4 d5 19. g5 Ne8 20. f4 Qe7 21.
exd5 cxd5 22. Nxd5 Rxd5 23. Qxd5 Qxe2 24. Qxb7) 17. f4 Qe6 18. e5 {We will not
continue this game. This is completely winning for White already.} Nh5 19. g3
g6 20. Bc4 Qf5+ 21. Bd3 Qe6 22. Nb5 Qxb3 23. exd6 cxd6 24. Rhe1 Nc6 25. Qc2
Qxc2+ 26. Bxc2 d5 27. Nc7 Ra5 28. Re8+ Rxe8 29. Nxe8 d4 30. Nd6 Nf6 31. Bb3 Kg7
32. Nxb7 Rh5 33. Nd6 Rxh2 34. Rc1 Na5 35. Bxf7 Ne4 36. Nxe4 Kxf7 37. b4 Nb3 38.
Rc6 d3 39. Rd6 d2 40. Kc2 Na1+ 41. Kc3 Rg2 42. Rxd2 Rg1 43. Kb2 Ke6 44. Rd3 Kf5
45. Nd6+ Kg4 46. a4 h5 47. a5 bxa5 48. bxa5 Re1 49. a6 Re7 50. Kxa1 1-0

