1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Qe2 d6 $6 {Again,
this typical mistake.} (6... a5 $5 7. a4 Nge7 8. Be3 Bxe3 9. Qxe3 Nb4 10. Na3
O-O 11. O-O-O $14) 7. Nc3 {is very slightly more accurate than Be3.} Nge7 {
This is a better version for Black than Nf6 because at least she has some f5
idea at her disposal just to have some energetic pawn play. But again, this d6
appears to be a bit slow.} 8. Be3 O-O 9. O-O-O {Black should play f5 here
which is a theoretical position. Instead, she took.} Bxe3+ 10. Qxe3 {And we
reached this typical structure once again. However, slightly better for Black
than before. Black is only slightly worse now because her knight is on e7 and
not f6 so she has f5 with some counterplay at a good moment. Black played} a5 (
{How about this pawn push} 10... a6 {[%cal Gb7b5] with the idea b5? Again, it
is not so effective. We will continue with} 11. f4 {and after} b5 {maybe a
move like} 12. Be2 {or Bd3} b4 {Most likely we will play} 13. Nd5 {The
computer sometimes even likes Na4. I would say that this b5-advance is maybe
slightly better than a5 which is totally pointless.}) {White played} 11. a3 $16
{which is another typical reaction.} ({However, the computer insists on this
very strange move} 11. Nd2 $3 $16 {giving a huge advantage for White. I would
say we don't play moves that we don't really understand. So far we have said
that the most typical move after a5 is Nd4 and this is what we should play
with some nice advantage for White.} f5 12. Bc4+ Kh8 13. f4 fxe4 14. Ndxe4 $16)
({We already talked about the move} 11. Nd4 $1 {is good enough for an
advantage especially if the knight was on f6. For example,} Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Nc6
13. Qd2 $16 {or even Qe3. Do you need to memorize any of these moves?
Absolutely not. Here, again, White has a nice advantage. For example} Be6 (
13... f5 {we take it.} 14. exf5 Bxf5 {Taking this diagonal with} 15. Bc4+ {
[%csl Gc4][%cal Ga2g8] is sometimes very good, very crucial. The computer
likes it very much as long as our bishop can remain on this diagonal.} Kh8 {
So here the best move would have been either} 16. a3 $16 {Our next move is
going to be f4 if we are allowed and stabilize our Bc4.} ({or maybe} 16. f4 {
I would say that with f4 I have to be careful about} Nb4 {such moves. We are
not playing chess alone.}) 16... Ne5 ({For example,} 16... Qd7 17. f4 {White
is clearly better. He has this d5-outpost where he can put the knight or the
bishop. Even Bb5 can be an interesting idea. Black has absolutely no attack
against our king. However, because Black played f5, the position in the centre
has kind of opened which means that the value of our flank attack with g4 or
h3-g4 is not so high anymore. So what we need to do is to play a couple of
moves in the centre, maybe I put the rook on the e-file and these h3 + g4
moves will be played most likely but a bit later. They will mostly have the
meaning of gaining space on the kingside rather than hoping for a checkmate
because the centre is open after the move f5. White is still better but for
different reasons not because he has checkmate ideas with h3-g4.}) 17. Be2 Qd7
18. f4 Ng4 19. Bf3 $16) 14. Kb1) 11... a4 12. Nd4 Bd7 {The only question is:
How big is White's advantage? f3 appears to be a bit slow to me. I want to
play f3-g4 if I see a knight on f6 and then I am ready to chase that knight
away. At this moment, I would possibly play Be2 intending g4. Of course, we
are not forced to know any theory here. It would be totally pointless. I am
all the moves lead to an advantage for White. Which one is better? Only the
computer knows.} 13. f4 {And again, White is much better.} ({Let me remind you
of this move:} 13. Ndb5 {This is an important move to keep both pairs of
knights. Of course, this move would be pointless if he could play a6 but he
cannot. Ndb5 should be considered but in this case, it is slightly risky
because we move the same piece again and again.}) ({If I ask a computer, I am
sure he will like} 13. Bc4 {very much for one move to prevent f5 and to
develop the position on this diagonal.}) 13... Re8 14. Bc4 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Nc6
16. Qf2 {I am sure Qd3 and Qd2 are also good.} Na5 ({Previously, there was a
question about exchanging pieces.} 16... Bg4 {No, I would not like to play} 17.
Be2 $2 {we are exchanging way too much.} ({In this position, in fact, a much
better move is} 17. Rde1) ({or maybe even} 17. Rd2 {[%cal Rf4f5] This is much
better and now we are already threatening f5.} Be6 {Here I would have played}
18. Bb5 {a la Carlsen and maybe even capture on a4. The only question is how
big White's advantage is.}) 17... Bxe2 18. Qxe2 {Let me tell you a little
secret: It is generally very good for us to push on the kingside with a gain
of tempo. g4-g5 - we would very much like to see a knight on f6 when we attack
it. Here our attack is kind of slow although White is still slightly better as
Black has absolutely no attack.}) 17. Ba2 b5 18. e5 dxe5 19. Ne4 Qe7 20. f5 Ra6
21. Rhf1 Nc4 22. f6 gxf6 23. Bxc4 bxc4 24. Nxf6+ Rxf6 25. Qxf6 Qxf6 26. Rxf6
Be6 27. g4 Kg7 28. g5 c6 29. Re1 Bd5 30. h4 c3 31. bxc3 e4 32. c4 Bxc4 33. Rxc6
Bd5 34. Rc5 Ba8 35. Kd2 Rb8 36. Rf1 Rd8+ 37. Ke3 Rd7 38. Rf6 Bd5 39. h5 Kf8 40.
Rb6 Ke7 41. c4 Be6 42. Kxe4 Rd1 43. Rc7+ Kd8 44. Ra7 Kc8 45. Rxe6 Re1+ 46. Kd4
1-0

