1. e4 ({This Ndb5 move idea actually exists in several other openings. Let me
show you a typical example:} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O
6. Nge2 e5 7. Be3 exd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 {9.Ndb5 here would be pointless.} 9. Qd2 a5
{This is a typical mistake. Now} 10. Ndb5 {is very strong with a similar idea.
We put pressure on the d6-point and Black is not able to chase the knight away
so the knight sits there keeping Black's position very passive, the queen
needs to stay on d8, and White is better.}) 1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4.
Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Qf6 {This is, in fact, an interesting idea after 6.
Nc3 threatening checkmate.} 7. Qe2 {[%cal Gc3d5] This is the only move and now
White is, of course, threatening Nd5.} Nge7 {Nd5 is not good, according to the
computer. Here, White played} 8. Be3 $5 ({If you would like to study some
theory} 8. h4 $5 {[%cal Gc1g5] is also an interesting possibility threatening
Bg5.} h6 ({For example,} 8... d6 9. Bg5 {with a fast development.} Qe6 10.
O-O-O h6 11. Be3 {We are out of book but not out of our ideas. Again, we would
like to exchange dark-squared bishops and start pushing our pawns. For example}
Bd7 (11... Bxe3+ 12. Qxe3 a6 13. f4 $36) {A million moves can be played. Maybe}
12. Bxb6 axb6 13. Qe3 {Restoring the coordination, or maybe even Qd2.} O-O-O
14. Nd4 {These types of positions will be studied with long castling for Black.
} Nxd4 15. Qxd4) 9. g4 (9. Bg5 $4 hxg5 10. hxg5 Qxf2+ $19 (10... Qxc3+)) 9...
d6 (9... Nd4 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Bd2 a6 12. f3 $36) 10. f4 $36 Qe6 11. Bh3) {
This move is wrong. In fact, Black should strive for long castling.} 8... O-O
$6 {and now he is worse although he won in the end.} (8... Bxe3 {All these
moves are wrong.} 9. Qxe3 {Maybe we are even threatening Nb5 here.} a6 10.
O-O-O {And we have a free hand.} d6 11. Be2 {or a million other moves.} ({
Let me give another example:} 11. f4 Bg4 12. Be2 {After this, White, again, is
better.} ({However, we need to keep more pieces on the board now.} 12. Rd2 {
[%csl Rg4][%cal Gh2h3] We will use this bishop on g4 to gain tempi.})) 11...
Bd7 12. f4 O-O-O 13. g4 $14 {White has, at least, a small advantage. Black can
play like this when he doesn't know the basic principles that Black urgently
needs to break with d5 or f5. Otherwise, he is left without his own play. When
our opponent has no pawn breaks it means that his rooks are inactive. That is
the problem. Here, Black's rooks are much more inactive than White's. White
can push h4 and g5 and there is a lot of space behind for his rooks. Whereas
Black's rooks are suffocating because there are no pawn breaks. If we remove
all four rooks, then White only has a very small advantage. So we don't need
to say much about the Qf6 line. We just exchange the bishops and we are better.
} ({Or} 13. Kb1 $14)) ({Black should have played for long castling with} 8...
d6 9. O-O-O Bd7 10. Bxb6 axb6 11. Qd2 O-O-O 12. f4 (12. Bb5 $14)) 9. O-O-O d6 {
Which idea for White is best now? Every time, you will think over the board.
Only the computer can definitely know the answer.} 10. h3 (10. Kb1 {is always
useful. After this move, we want to play f4. There is no rule of thumb when to
play Kb1. I would say that whenever we feel some danger on various diagonals
this is when we should play Kb1.} Be6 11. f4 Bxe3 12. Qxe3 $16 Rad8 13. Qf3 $1
$16 Ng6 14. g3 Nge5 15. Qg2 Ng4 16. Qe2 $18) ({Just} 10. f4 $4 {we need to
avoid. Too much enthusiasm.} Bg4 {Now Black is winning a pawn for nothing. So
we always need to be careful.}) ({Another possibility is} 10. Qd2 {restoring,
once again, the coordination.}) 10... Be6 11. f4 Qh4 12. Kb1 f5 13. Bxb6 axb6
14. Nb5 fxe4 15. Nxc7 Bxb3 16. cxb3 Rac8 17. Ne6 Rf6 18. Qxe4 d5 19. Qe1 Qh6
20. Ng5 Rxf4 21. h4 Qf6 22. g3 Rf2 23. Rd2 Rxd2 24. Qxd2 h6 25. Bh3 Rf8 26. Ne6
Qg6+ 27. Ka1 Rf3 28. Bg2 Rd3 29. Qe2 Qxg3 30. Rf1 Re3 31. Qd2 Rxe6 32. Bxd5
Nxd5 33. Qxd5 Qe5 0-1

