{the forced play variation with a fast Nf6-0-0 without d6!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6
3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 {Usually, Carlsen would play 6.Qe2 but here
he played} 6. Nc3 Nf6 {Indeed, this is a very interesting possibility, the
most straightforward approach! Now, we enter concrete play. Why?} 7. Qe2 O-O $5
{black has not wasted time with d6..so in some lines, he wants to go for a
quick d7-d5} (7... d6 8. Be3) {That's why Carlsen played} 8. Bg5 $1 {[%cal
Gc3d5] Now there is a threat of Nd5.} (8. Be3 {This is a possibility. Black
only has one good move here:} d5 $1 {This is theory.} ({Your opponent may as
well play} 8... d6 {and end up much worth after, for example,} 9. O-O-O) (8...
a5 {I am not even sure if we take on b6 here.} 9. a4 {Let's have a look here.}
Bxe3 10. Qxe3 Nb4 {Again, we castle long} 11. O-O-O {I believe there is no d5
so} d6 {such a move, and now, again, we have chances:} 12. f3 {[%cal Gg2g4]
intending g4 and everything. After} Be6 {I would have possibly played} 13. Nd4
({But also} 13. g4 {might be interesting.} Bxb3 14. cxb3 {Yes, the knight on
b4 is strong but it is not backed up by the rest of the pieces. Possibly 13.
Nd4 would have been better.})) 9. O-O-O d4 $132 {This is an unclear position
with chances for both sides which I suggest we avoid.}) 8... h6 {This is the
only move.} (8... Re8 $2 9. Nd5 $3 $16 {now White is almost winning.}) ({
The same goes for} 8... d6 {and} 9. Nd5 $16) ({After,} 8... d6 {I have to say
that 9.Nd5 is much better for White. However, we could even play} 9. O-O-O {
and if he goes} h6 {Look what happens if you know these positions:} 10. Be3 {
First of all, you know that this is a very good position for White because
this h6 move is a hook and later it will help us with our attack.} Re8 11. f3 {
For example,} Bxe3+ 12. Qxe3 {and} a5 {it is needless to even say that} 13. Nd4
{highlights the absence of meaning of this a5.}) 9. Bh4 a5 {now White needs to
play} 10. a4 Nd4 {and we get this kind of concrete line.} ({If} 10... d6 {
then 11.Nd5 is not so strong anymore because of g5. Even if we are lost and
don't remember the theory we can always play positional chess based on the
principles.} 11. O-O-O Re8 12. f3 {We want to attack with g4 and everything. I
believe that White has very good chances, for example} Be6 13. g4 $36 ({Even} 
13. Bf2 $5 {is very interesting strategically speaking.} Bxf2 14. Qxf2 {
We know by now that such a position, especially if d5 is not working and it
doesn't appear to be, we know that White is better here. For example,} Nb4 (
14... Bxb3 15. cxb3 Nb4 16. g4 $36) {We are already out of book but we know
exactly what to do.} 15. Nd4 $16)) {Carlsen replied with the best move} 11. Qd3
Nxb3 12. cxb3 {and we get to this semi-forced position.} Re8 ({Theoretically
speaking,} 12... c6 $5 {is the best move} 13. O-O-O {and} d5 {Now, White has
various possibilities. I believe that} 14. Qc2 $5 {just like Carlsen played,
is again the best, and we have some nice chances.} Be6 (14... d4 15. f3 Be6 16.
Ne2 $36) 15. Kb1 $14 (15. exd5 cxd5 16. Nxd5 $1 Bxd5 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Rxd5 $14
Qxf2 (18... Rad8 19. Rf5 $3 Qg6 20. g3 Rd6 (20... Rfe8 21. Bc4) 21. Bc4 $16)
19. Qxf2 Bxf2 20. Bc4 $14 b6 21. Rd7 Bc5 22. Rf1)) 13. O-O-O d6 {In fact,
White is better here by force:} 14. Qc2 $14 {is very strong. Why? Carlsen won
very convincingly here because he has this c4-square, he has a nice attack on
the kingside.} Bd7 15. Bc4 Be6 16. Rhe1 Qe7 17. e5 dxe5 18. Rxe5 Qf8 19. Bxf6
gxf6 20. Re2 Qg7 21. Bxe6 Rxe6 22. Rxe6 fxe6 23. Rd3 Kh8 24. Rg3 Qh7 25. Qd2
Bc5 26. Ne4 Be7 27. Rh3 Kg7 28. Qd7 Kf7 29. Ng5+ fxg5 30. Rf3+ Kg8 31. Qxe6+
Kh8 32. Rf7 Bd6 33. Rxh7+ Kxh7 34. Qf7+ Kh8 35. g3 Ra6 36. Kb1 Bb4 37. f4 gxf4
38. gxf4 1-0

