{It is a mistake to play a4 by ourselves. Why? For a very deep reason:} 1. e4
e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 Nge7 7. a4 $6 {No, this
move is not so good. If White plays a4, the correct move is, in fact} a6 $1 {
This is a very good move for Black. What is the problem now for White? When we
castle short, it is not good for us anyway. Black has a very active game. His
bishop from b6 is very, very strong so castling short is out of the question.
We want to castle long. But after this a4-a6, Black is adding dynamics. He
hasn't played a5 so it is quite possible for Black to play b5 at some moment
while we will castle long. That is the problem with a4. We cannot castle short
because then we have no claim for an advantage; and if we castle long, this b5
is always a potential threat.} 8. a5 Ba7 {How can you castle long with a pawn
on a5? We usually don't do that.} 9. Qe2 O-O 10. Bg5 (10. Be3 Bxe3 11. Qxe3 d6
12. O-O-O Be6 13. Nd5 f5 $132) 10... f6 11. Bh4 d6 {Black had a very nice game
and this pawn on a5 would only help Black.} 12. O-O-O Ng6 13. Bg3 f5 14. f3 f4
15. Bf2 Bxf2 16. Qxf2 Be6 17. h4 Bxb3 18. cxb3 Nxa5 19. h5 Ne5 20. h6 Nxb3+ 21.
Kc2 Nc5 22. hxg7 Kxg7 23. Rh5 Qf6 24. Nd5 Qf7 25. Qh4 Kh8 26. Be2 Rg8 27. Rh1
Rg7 28. Qf6 Kg8 29. Qh4 Rf8 30. Bf1 c6 31. Rg5 Rxg5 32. Qxg5+ Kh8 33. Ne7 Qf6
34. Ng6+ Nxg6 35. Qh6 Qg7 0-1

