Once again, a bit inaccurate.} a6 {is the correct move. There is nowhere
really good to go with our king now. For example, he played} 8. Nd5 $6 {
Not a good move anyway.} (8. Bf4 d6 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Be6 11. Nd5 Ba7 12. f3
(12. Kb1 Qd7 (12... f5) 13. f3 f5 $36) 12... f5 $36 13. Bc4 Ng6) 8... Nxd5 {
This is good.} (8... Ba7 $5 {But this is good enough.} 9. Bg5 d6 {For example,
we try} 10. Qe2 {but nothing is really happening here. Black is solid enough.}
O-O 11. O-O-O h6 12. Bh4 {In fact, the computer finds this incredible move:}
Qd7 $3 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gf7f5,Yb7b5,Yd7a4] Black is ready to play Ng6 or f5. And,
of course, the queen is targeting the a4-pawn. And of course, all the time b5
advances are in the air. We clearly feel that the a4-pawn has nothing to do
there and should have been on a2.} ({This a4 move resembles} 12... g5 13. Bg3 {
for Black. Black says that his computer claims that this is -0.11 But in a
practical game, with these g5 and h6 pawns, we can break with f4 or h4 and we
will deliver checkmate.}) 13. Nc3 (13. f3 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nb4) 13... f5 $15) 9.
exd5 Qf6 10. Qe2+ Ne7 11. h4 h6 12. Bd2 O-O 13. a5 Ba7 14. Bc3 Qd6 15. O-O-O
