{the plan with 0-0-0 by black} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5.
Nb3 Bb6 ({By the way, I analyzed} 5... Bb4+ {You know, when you know the ideas
you can think for yourself and produce very nice ideas. After} 6. c3 ({I tell
you one thing: After} 6. Bd2 {so it happens that Black has this very good move
6...a5 here. However, theoretically, if that was not possible, we could play}
Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 {and he would end up much worse. Our development is very fast
and, in fact, our queen is ideally placed on d2 and not on e2.} Nf6 {A further
mistake.} 8. Nc3 d6 9. O-O-O O-O 10. f3 {And we already know that White is
much better because we reached this type of game. Now, we know exactly what to
do. We know that we are better. We know that after} a5 {we play} 11. Nd4 {
most likely. We are aware of this idea.} Re8 {Yes, we can play} 12. g4 ({
We can also play} 12. Ndb5 {and we are much better.})) 6... Be7 {White has
some advantage now.} 7. c4 {is good.} ({And} 7. f4 {is good.})) 6. Nc3 Nf6 {
So far so good. This is much better than 6...d6.} (6... d6 7. Qe2 Nf6 8. Be3
Be6 {is the other move order}) 7. Qe2 d6 {This d6 we already mentioned is not
so good. At least, Black should castle long.} 8. Be3 {White is better. However,
Black should choose a quiet set-up. Black should castle long. So far we have
examined by the games of Carlsen castling short and he will castle long, then
play f3, Qd2 and so on and he is simply better.} Qe7 {So Black should castle
long. Again, Black is worse although Black in this game played brilliantly and
she won.} 9. O-O-O Be6 {It doesn't matter if the computer can somehow equalize.
} (9... Nxe4 $4 {This is not hanging, of course.} 10. Nd5 $18) ({How about the
move} 9... Bd7 {This is wrong. Black does not even threaten d5 now. So I would
say} 10. g3 {might be possible.} ({However, we can easily see that} 10. f3 {
is also possible here.} O-O-O {We are out of book, I can tell you that.} (10...
Bxe3+ 11. Qxe3 O-O {After} 12. g4 {[%csl Rd7] White is almost winning because
also the Bd7 is horribly placed. After} a5 {I will calculate} 13. g5 {because
his position is way too bad.} ({Otherwise, I will play} 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4
Qe5 {Yes, this is dropping a piece, I can take} 15. Qxe5 ({If we suppose that
he was not dropping a piece, I would have played} 15. Qd2 {with a huge
advantage.}) ({I have to tell you that} 15. Be2 Qxd4 16. Rxd4 {[%cal Gg4g5,
Gh2h4] such an endgame is generally better for White because g5, h4 and this
a5 move is totally random.}) 15... dxe5 16. g5 {[%csl Rd7]})) 11. Bxb6 axb6 12.
g4 {is interesting.} (12. Qd2 {restoring coordination is also interesting here
and we are doing really great. Again, he is left without play.} Rhe8 {We will
think. Kb1, g4. I believe it is clear by now that knowing these types of
positions, knowing why we are better and how is much more important than
memorizing lines.}))) {How about this move} 10. f3 {No, this move is not so
good. First of all, this f3-g4 is maybe not our first priority now that she is
going to castle long as it seems. There is another thing that we need to
mention. When she castles long, her rook is put immediately on the d-line so
the move d6-d5 comes very fast. It is impossible to prevent this break. in
fact this is a bit slow...black has many chances to play d6-d5 at some point..
and equalize or even get the initiative!} ({What to do here?} 10. g3 $1 {
this is the best in my view! If you ask the computer, it will give a very
small plus for White and will make accurate moves for Black and after many
moves equalize. Otherwise, we would say that White is winning. White is not
winning here. We are slightly better does not mean we are winning.} O-O-O (
10... Nd7 $6 11. Bg2 O-O-O 12. Rhe1 Rhe8 13. Kb1 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Nb6 15. Nd4 $14)
11. Bxb6 $1 {I prefer to play this move, in fact, to double the pawns.} ({
Although} 11. Bg2 $5 $14 {is also possible, again, with a small advantage.}
Rhe8 (11... Bxe3+ 12. Qxe3 Kb8 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 $14)) 11... axb6 12. Bg2 {
There is not much to see here. Our next moves are Rhe1, we need to be careful
about that f4 advance because Bg4 may force us to exchange pieces and maybe
even e4 will be weak so we need to be more careful.} Rhe8 13. Qd2 $5 {[%cal
Gf2f4,Yd1e1,Ye6g4,Gc1b1,Yc3d5] I would suggest that this is an even better
move. The point is that after f4 Bg4 we simply want to play Rde1. Here we want
to play Kb1, the usual stuff, Rhe1, put our pieces in the centre, Nd5 is
hanging in the air at any moment. White is clearly slightly better.} ({Yes,} 
13. Nd4 $5 {is good. First choice by the computer and mentioned in some books.}
Nxd4 14. Rxd4 {White is slightly better.} Kb8 15. Rhd1 $14 h6 16. a4 $5 (16.
Kb1)) 13... Ne5 $2 {Ne5-c4 is hardly ever a threat when we have such a great
defence ...the Nc4 does not work together with the rest of the pieces!} ({
I analyzed such a move} 13... Kb8 {briefly.} 14. f4 $14 {We don't need much to
see.} Nd7 (14... Bg4 {we simply put our pieces here} 15. Rde1 {[%cal Gc1b1,
Gh2h3,Gg3g4,Gf4f5,Ge4e5,Yc3d5] White is just better. Why? Because Black does
not have pawn play whereas we have pawn play h3, g4, f5, e5; Nd5. All these
moves are on the agenda.}) 15. Nd4 (15. Kb1 f6 16. Bf3 Nc5 17. Rhe1 $14) 15...
Nxd4 16. Qxd4 f6 17. b3 $1 Nc5 18. Kb2 $14) 14. f4 Nc4 15. Qe2 $18 {Here, in
fact, the computer is saying that White is winning. I wouldn't say that.} Na5 {
might be possible. Again, we know that we may just take it} 16. Nxa5 ({Or we
may play a move like} 16. Nd4 {and after that, we calculate} Bg4 {of course
because that may be strong.}) 16... bxa5 17. Qb5 {and start calculating
tactics.} ({If Qb5 is not working, we may play} 17. h3 {[%cal Gg3g4]}) (17. Bf3
{protecting everything. White is clearly better. There are no plans for Black.}
)) ({Even} 10. Qd2 $5 {is good restoring the coordination of the pieces...is
always practical and good!} O-O-O (10... O-O $5 11. Re1 $1 {stoping d5} Bxe3
12. Rxe3) ({Instead of castling, can Black take and castle long then?} 10...
Bxe3 11. Qxe3 O-O-O {No, because there are problems with a7.} 12. Bb5) 11. Bxb6
axb6 12. Nd5 $3 {This is kind of concrete. White does have a small advantage.}
Bxd5 13. exd5 Ne5 14. Bb5 $3 $16 {I analyzed this briefly Bb5 is a very strong
move because c6 we take, take and Ba6+.}) 10... O-O-O 11. Bxb6 {This makes a
lot of sense because} axb6 {now b5 is kind of a strong square now. However,
this is not the most important element of the game. The most important thing
is to push d5.} 12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 Rhe8 {Indeed, very fast development.} 14.
Qe3 d5 $1 $36 {Black is doing great. In a practical sense, Black is already
better.} 15. Bb5 ({White should consider taking} 15. exd5 {and trying to
equalize.} Nxd5 (15... Qc5 $5)) 15... c6 16. exd5 {However, all of a sudden}
Qc5 $1 {a brilliant move based on tactics, pinning all the pieces, d6 is not
possible, the rook drops. So here, White can keep equality with very precise
moves.} 17. Na4 $2 {after this, she is, in fact, losing by force.} Bxd5 $3 $19
18. Qf4 (18. Qxe8 {was also completely lost in several ways. Black can even
take} Qxd4 {and this is just lost as the pieces are dropping.}) 18... Qxb5 {
and simply losing a piece.} 19. Rb4 Re4 20. Qf5+ Be6 21. Qxb5 cxb5 22. Nxb6+
Kc7 23. fxe4 Kxb6 24. a4 Bc4 25. axb5 Kc5 26. c3 Nxe4 27. Rd1 Rxd1+ 28. Kxd1 f5
