1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 {Or 6.Qe2, yes
you make a choice but the ideas remain the same. There are two ways for Black
to play the system with Nge7: Nge7, 0-0 and a very fast f5 or Nge7, 0-0, d6
and at some moment f5. Let's divide it into two sub-systems "the fast Nge7+f5
and "the slow Nge7+f5". Now we will see the slow Nge7+f5 which means that
Black added the move d6. In fact, this system is very popular, it is quite
playable but I do believe that White has a small advantage for sure. So, I
would suggest for Black two ideas so far: Either Nf6 concrete system or he
should play with castle long. Or he should play Nge7, 0-0 and a very fast f5.
Let's see:} d6 7. Qe2 {I will put it in order from the worst one to the best
one for Black here. 6...d6 was already a mistake. - The worst that Black can
do is play Nf6 and 0-0. - The second worst is to play Nf6 and 0-0-0. - The
third, and possibly best thing by this moment, he can do is Nge7 and f5, the
slow f5 with d6 inserted.} Nge7 8. Be3 {Generally, it is good for us to
exchange dark-squared bishops, as we said.} O-O 9. O-O-O f5 {Yes, this is an
important theoretical position. White usually plays g3 or something. There are
easier ways for White to handle this.} ({I will create another example by
myself: Let's suppose he takes} 9... Bxe3+ 10. Qxe3 Re8 {Too slow.} ({And he
plays} 10... Be6 {We can play} 11. f4 {with some advantage because he is late
with the f5 move.} ({Or I can play} 11. Be2 {We do know what to do after a5.}
Qd7 {[%cal Gb3c5] may even run into a move like Nc5.} (11... Ne5 {This is
totally wrong, we have seen this already.} 12. f4 Nc4 {This knight is doing
nothing on c4. We can take it or ignore it.} 13. Bxc4 {I can take it} Bxc4 {and
} 14. g4 ({Or play} 14. Nd4)) ({Let's suppose he plays a move like} 11... a6 {
A very interesting idea now is} 12. g4 {intending to stop f5 once and for all,
and then try for f4 and everything.})) ({I tried to make} 11. g4 {ideas work,
this gambit. And if he takes, f3, Be2 or something. I tried to play in various
positions while training with the computer. I tried to play g4. Unfortunately,
it would never work. The computer would always give an advantage to Black. So,
maybe this g4 is too much. Of course, there is some compensation - but maybe
it is too much. So it is better to play a move like 11.f4})) 11. f4 {is good
for White.} Bg4 {I wouldn't exchange but} 12. Be2 Bxe2 13. Qxe2 {even here we
are better with a small advantage.} Qd7 14. g4 $16 a5 15. a4 $16 Nb4 16. Kb1)
10. f3 $6 {This is not a solution.} (10. Bxb6 $3 {SOS !! A VERY VERY IMPORTANT
LINE TO REMEMBER! ....THIS IS HOW YOU MUST PLAY AGAINST THE...Nge7 and ...SLOW
f5 PLAN! (d6 and f5)} axb6 11. exf5 {It is usually advantageous for Black to
take on e4. We need to take on f5 first.} Bxf5 {Now we need to stabilize the
position. Of course, our queen will not remain there. Our queen will either be
put on d2 or we will play g3 and Bg2.} 12. a3 $1 {In my view, this is the best
move because there are some ideas with Nb4 with double attacks.} (12. g3 Kh8
13. a3 (13. Bg2 Nb4) 13... Qd7 14. Bg2 Rae8 15. Qb5 Bg6 16. f4) {He needs to
play a move like} 12... Kh8 {sooner or later.} 13. f4 (13. g3 $14 Qd7 14. Bg2)
({Now, for example} 13. Qd2 $14 {[%cal Gf1b5] restoring coordination and White
is fighting for a small advantage. I would say a player up to 2500 should know
up to this point. Qd2 with a possible Bb5 and then he should start thinking by
himself. White has a small advantage, slightly easier play, and the game
continues. This is a very important line that you need to remember against the
fast Nge7 f5 idea. Of course, there are a million moves Black can play here,
for example:} Qd7 ({The computer may also suggest} 13... Qe8 {for example. We
can play} 14. Bb5 Qf7 15. f3 {Put our pieces in the centre.} h6 {Be careful
not to do} 16. Kb1 ({Possibly we will start with} 16. h4) ({Or} 16. Rhe1 {
and we have nice play in the centre. In the long run, we will push g4, f4-f5,
h4 all these moves. But as I said, because the centre is open, these attacks
are not meant to deliver checkmate because the centre is open, the flank
attack loses its value. These moves are meant to gain space and maybe very
slowly create some mating threats.}) 16... Qxb3 {and lose your knight.}) 14.
Bb5 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gh2h3,Gg2g4] we can play f4 next move and start pushing
with h3-g4.} Rad8 15. Rhe1) 13... Qd7 14. Qd2 $14 Rae8 15. Bb5) 10... f4 11.
Bxb6 axb6 12. g3 Ng6 13. Nd5 Qg5 (13... Rxa2 $19) (13... Nce5 $17 14. Kb1 fxg3
$17) 14. Kb1 fxg3 15. Nxc7 Ra4 16. Nd5 Nf4 17. Qb5 Rb4 18. Nxb4 g2 19. Bc4+ d5
20. Rhg1 Na7 21. Bxd5+ Nxd5 22. Qxd5+ Qxd5 23. Nxd5 Bh3 24. Nxb6 Rxf3 25. Rde1
Rf1 26. c4 Nc6 27. Nd7 h6 28. e5 Nb4 29. e6 Nd3 30. Rexf1 gxf1=Q+ 31. Rxf1 Bxf1
32. Nd4 Nf4 33. e7 Kf7 34. Nf5 Bxc4 35. Ne5+ Ke8 36. Nxc4 Nd5 37. Ncd6+ Kd7 38.
e8=Q+ Kc7 39. Qc8+ Kb6 40. Nd4 Ka7 41. N6b5+ Kb6 42. Qd8+ Kc5 43. Qf8+ 1-0

