{Now let's go to the other very good system for Black which is the fast
Nge7+f5 system. So far, how should Black counter this Nb3 system? Two good
ways I see: The concrete Nf6 after he studies it a lot, and the fast Nge7+f5
system which we will see right now.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5
5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3 {Or starting with 6.Qe2 first.} Nge7 7. Qe2 ({I need to tell
you, however, that I will offer you a very valuable alternative for White here.
This alternative exists in the 6.Nc3 move order, with the 6.Qe2 mover order it
is not possible.} 7. Bf4 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] is a very interesting idea for
White to analyze. This is a totally playable system. The computer kind of
likes it. Now we won't play Qe2, of course, but we will play Qd2 next move.
For example,} d6 8. Qd2 {Not Qe2. We only play Qe2 to play Be3.} O-O 9. O-O-O {
and we intend to play f3 and g4. Black should still play some f5 idea. We do
have this Be3 idea at some moment. If he goes} a5 {There is no Nd4 now. So we
are restricted to two options. Either} 10. a4 ({or this idea} 10. Bb5 {
depending on the situation.})) 7... O-O 8. Be3 {Can he play 8...d5? No. 8...d5
is working with Nf6. Here after 8...d5 9.0-0-0 he is losing.} f5 {or directly.
This is a totally playable possibility and a very good system for Black.} ({
So Black here needs to either play} 8... d6 {but that is slow.} 9. O-O-O f5 {
and as we mentioned, here, in my view, the best move is} 10. Bxb6 axb6 11. exf5
Bxf5 ({and if} 11... Nxf5 {possibly} 12. Qd2 {restoring coordination with a
small advantage for White and a playable interesting game.}) 12. a3 {[%cal
Ge2d2] and Qd2.}) {Now 9.exf5 is interesting, keep that in mind. However, we
castle} 9. O-O-O {We clearly want to take on f5. If he goes d6, we go to the
slow Nge7+f5 system. However, unfortunately, it is Black's turn and he has two
interesting possibilities.} fxe4 {White played} 10. Bxb6 ({Now we need to take
here directly.} 10. Nxe4 {This is the best move. Again, the ideas are the same.
But generally, we prefer to take on f5 rather than to allow him to take on e4.
For example,} d6 11. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2] Followed by Bg2 and we try to reach a
similar position as with the knight on c3. But now there is counterplay for
Black. He managed to play f5, opening up his rook and his pieces.} Kh8 (11...
Ne5 12. h3 Nf5 13. Bxb6 axb6 14. a3 Bd7 15. f4 Nf7 16. Qf2 $14 Bc6 17. Bg2 $16)
12. Bg2 $14 Bf5 13. a3) 10... axb6 11. Qxe4 {He didn't know any theory.} d6 ({
And after} 11... Rxf2 {it doesn't seem that White has enough compensation.})
12. Bc4+ Kh8 13. Rhe1 Rxf2 14. Nd4 Nxd4 $2 (14... Bd7 $17) 15. Rxd4 Nc6 16. Qh4
Rf8 17. Qxd8 Nxd8 18. Nd5 Nc6 19. Rf4 Bd7 20. Rxf8+ Rxf8 21. Nxc7 Rf2 22. Be6
Bxe6 23. Rxe6 h5 24. Rxd6 Rxg2 25. h3 h4 26. Rd8+ Kh7 27. Rd7 Rg3 28. Ne6 Ne5
29. Rxb7 Nf3 30. b3 Kh6 31. Rxb6 Kh5 32. Nf4+ Kg5 33. Ne6+ Kf5 34. Nc7 g5 35.
a4 Rxh3 36. a5 Rh1+ 37. Kb2 h3 38. a6 h2 39. a7 Rb1+ 40. Kxb1 h1=Q+ 41. Kb2 Nd2
42. a8=Q Qb1+ 43. Kc3 Ne4+ 44. Kb4 Qe1+ 45. Kb5 Nc3+ 46. Ka6 Ne4 47. Qd5+ Kf4
48. Ne6+ Kg4 49. Qd4 Qf1+ 50. Ka7 Qf5 51. Rb4 Qf8 52. Nxf8 Kh5 53. Qxe4 g4 54.
Qxg4+ Kh6 55. Qg6# 1-0

