{Another interesting structure for Black with many games is the so-called
"Kamsky Variation". Gata Kamsky, the great grandmaster, has played this
several times.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 6. Nc3
Nge7 7. Qe2 (7. Bg5 {This is also interesting but after} f6 {the best White
can do is play} 8. Bf4 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gd8e8,Ge8f7] and he will transpose to the
Bf4 variation where this f6 move might be useful for Black. If you study the
lines, you will see that sometimes Black plays f6, 0-0, Qe8-f7. So he can do
that with tempo.}) 7... O-O 8. Be3 f5 9. O-O-O {It is interesting to even take
on f5.} f4 10. Bxb6 axb6 {This position. The computer tends to give a small
advantage to White. However, practically speaking, this is an unclear position
with chances to both sides because there is a clear positional concept for
Black: He has played f5-f4. He has secured the e5-square for his pieces. He
has this open a-line which may come in handy some time.} 11. g3 {Gata Kamsky
knows that this position is slightly better for White. But, nevertheless, he
has active piece play and in the end he won.} ({You can study this position
with a computer. But you don't need to know anything. For example,} 11. Kb1 {
such moves can be played.} d6 12. f3 {He has several ideas. Be6, Ng6, Ne5
first, or even Qe8 sometimes. You do not need to memorize much here. The
computer tends to like White's position.} Be6 (12... Ng6 13. Qd2 {Yes, White
appears to have a small advantage.} Be6 {or first. We have d4 for one knight,
d5 for the other knight. Our bishop can come to b5. With this f5-f4 Black has
stopped us from freely advancing on the kingside. Or idea, quite often, is to
play g3 to break the pawn structure and open up the position.} (13... Nge5 14.
Nd5 {both players appear to have strong knights.})) 13. Qd2 {Develop the
pieces in the centre and White has a small advantage no matter what. You need
to be careful and you need to know typical motives.} Ng6 14. Nd5 {If he takes}
Bxd5 ({He cannot play} 14... Nge5 {at the moment because he is losing a pawn}
15. Nxf4) ({Possibly, he can put the other knight to e5} 14... Nce5 {[%cal
Gc7c6] with c6 at some moment.} 15. Nd4 {and you get slightly better positions.
}) {we quite often take with the e-pawn.} 15. exd5 {[%cal Gb3d4]} Nce5 {
and play} 16. Nd4) 11... d6 12. gxf4 Rxf4 13. Rg1 Ne5 14. Nd4 Qf8 15. f3 c6 16.
Rg3 b5 17. a3 Qf6 18. Qe3 Rh4 19. Kb1 N7g6 20. Ndxb5 cxb5 21. Nd5 Qf8 22. f4
