1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 ({Another way to sometimes get similar positions is,
surprisingly, in the following line:} 2. Nc3 {The Vienna Game with a very
modern idea in this very ancient opening:} Nf6 3. d4 {White, in a level up to
2500, has tremendous scores with this move with similar play.} exd4 4. Qxd4 {
This is an interesting possibility to explore where you lose some tempi but
you gain the same structure.} Nc6 5. Qd3 Be7 ({Here} 5... Bc5 {we can,
unfortunately, not play Be3 for tactical reasons. We would like that very much.
} 6. Bf4 d6 7. Qd2 O-O 8. O-O-O a6 9. f3 {[%cal Gg2g4]} Be6 10. g4 (10. Be3 {
and it is not all impossible that at some moment we will play Be3, trade
dark-squared bishops and get similar structures.} Bxe3 11. Qxe3)) {For example,
here you can guess that the move is} 6. Bf4 {[%cal Ge1c1] and castle long with
very similar play.} d6 7. O-O-O O-O 8. f3 Nh5 9. Be3 Ne5 {Yes, all these tempi
are totally meaningless.} 10. Qd2 Be6 11. g4 {White is already winning.}) (2.
d4 exd4 3. Qxd4 Nc6 4. Qc4) 2... d6 (2... Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {
Theoretically, someone can play} d6 ({Or} 4... Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb4+ 6. c3 Be7) 5.
Nc3 Nf6) ({Let me adjust it, once again, to a Scotch game:} 2... Nc6 3. d4 exd4
4. Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Be7 6. Nc3 d6 {Yes, it is highly unlikely that you will
have this position. But you never know.} 7. Bf4 Nf6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O {
For example,} a5 10. Nd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 {Again, our plan is the same, f3 and g4
and everything h4 with a nice advantage.} Be6 12. f3 {If he tries} Nh5 13. Be3
Bg5 {But this is very much in vain because we know very well that} 14. Kb1 Bxe3
15. Qxe3 {trading dark-squared bishops is a vital idea for White.} Nf6 16. g4 {
Once again, starting from the Philidor, White ends up in the same pawn
structure with a big advantage. What we needed to point out was the very
important Bf4 move.}) 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 {Although we are
playing a Philidor, someone might say that it is almost like a Scotch. It is
very important to remember the move} 6. Bf4 {This is the key move in such
positions. This move belongs to f4. Why?} (6. Bg5 {here the bishop is doing
absolutely nothing, the knight is very well protected and, in fact, the bishop
is very vulnerable to tactics connected to Nxe4 at any moment. Or h6 Bh4 and
Nxe4. So the bishop is not active at all here.}) (6. Be3 {Again, this is very
vulnerable against Ng4 threats. This Ng4 tends to be very active and it offers
some tactical possibilities sooner or later.}) 6... O-O {Now we play} 7. Qd2 {
and if I had the bishop on e3, Ng4 would be very interesting and annoying
connected with some fast counterplay and tactics.} Nbd7 ({But with the bishop
on f4, trying to do the same with} 7... Nh5 {This can hardly ever be a good
move because all the time I will come} 8. Be3 {and no tactics can ever be
connected with a knight on h5. That's why the bishop belongs on f4 in such
positions.}) 8. O-O-O Nc5 9. f3 a5 10. g4 $16 Be6 11. Kb1 Nfd7 12. Nd5 (12. g5)
(12. h4) 12... Bh4 13. Nf5 $18 Bxf5 14. gxf5 Nf6 15. Nc3 Nh5 16. Be3 Nd7 17.
Rg1 Kh8 18. Qg2 Bf6 19. Nd5 g6 20. Nxf6 Ndxf6 21. Bd4 Qe7 22. Qg5 b5 23. Bxb5
Rab8 24. Be2 Rb4 25. Bc3 Rfb8 26. b3 Kg8 27. f4 Kf8 28. e5 Ne4 29. Qxe7+ Kxe7
30. f6+ Ke8 31. Bxb4 Nxf4 32. Bf3 Rxb4 33. Bxe4 Rxe4 34. exd6 Kd7 35. dxc7+
Kxc7 36. Rg5 Re6 37. Rxa5 Rxf6 38. Ra7+ Kb6 39. Rdd7 1-0

