{[%evp 0,10,25,24,16,16,16,9,9,9,19,10,10]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4.
Nxd4 Bc5 5. Nb3 Bb6 {CONCLUSIONS : 1) It is very bad ( but quite possible)
that Black will play a random d6?! on the very first moves followed by an even
worse ...Nf6 and ...0-0 and end up in a strategically lost position without
pawn breaks! 2) Generally, it is not good for us to go for an early a2-a4?!
because Black should reply with ...a6! ..and a future b7-b5 brake! 3) There
are 2 acceptable setups by Black a) the fast Nf6-0-0 concrete line..without...
.d6 b) The fast Nge7-0-0 -f5 line...without d6   4) in the slow Nge7-f5 line 
(together with d6) ..WE SHOULD CAPTURE ON f5 ..AND ON b6 ..AND PLAY a3-Qd2!
etc..........5) If Black goes for a fast 0-0-0, then, he'll have a rook on d8
very fast..so he will threaten d6-d5. Therefore, we should avoid the slow
f3-g4 plan and play g3!-Bg2! fighting against the d6-d5 advance 6) Generally,
when Black plays f7-f5, we prefer to take ef5..rather than allow fxe4 7) after
Black's a7-a5 advance, depending on the situation, we will replay with a2-a4...
or a2-a3...or Nb3-d4! ..which always gives an advantage. if it is possible! 7)
In the Bc5-Nb3! Scotch...almost always we play 0-0-0 ... and try to attack,
HOWEVER ..WE ARE OPEN MINDED...AND READY TO PLAY A BETTER ENDGAME...AT ANY
TIME !} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Typical Scotch Endgames"]
[Black "overview"]
