[Source "ChessPublishing"]

{[%evp 0,30,19,38,25,7,30,26,23,27,-10,-14,-15,0,24,6,24,2,9,4,16,14,12,-3,3,
-21,-20,-2,-14,-14,-14,7,19]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 {In this
lecture we will focus on typical endgames that arise from the Scotch Game.
Such endgames are usually characterised by the doubled c-pawns after the
exchange of knights on c6. We usually get this structure in the major
theoretical variations:} Nf6 ({and} 4... Bc5 5. Nxc6 Qf6 (5... bxc6) 6. Qf3
bxc6 ({or} 6... Qxf3 7. gxf3 bxc6 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7,Rf2,Rf3]})) 5. Nxc6 bxc6 {
[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7][%cal Yd7d5]} 6. e5 {[%csl Ye5] This move is essential in
order to prevent Black from easily improving his pawn structure with ...d5,
exd5 cxd5.} Qe7 7. Qe2 Nd5 8. c4 {We will mostly focus on endgames that arise
from this popular position of the Scotch Game. Black should keep in mind that
transition into the endgame means that not only the doubled c-pawns are a
potential liability, but also very often the isolated a-pawn. We will break
down the material based on the two major plans that Black has at his disposal
here: 1)} Nb6 ({and 2)} 8... Ba6 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gf7f6,Yd5f6] which allows
Black to keep the knight on d5 for a while and possibly also bring it back to
the kingside after ...f6, exf6 Nxf6. In that case, the endgame is usually not
so problematic for Black as in 8...Nb6 line because the knight has obviously
more freedom to move on f6 than on the b6-square. A good example is:} 9. Nd2 ({
Another interesting thematic endgame that we will explore arises after a
fairly forced sequence:} 9. b3 g6 10. g3 Bg7 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Bg2 Rae8 13. O-O
Bxe5 14. Qxe5 Qxe5 15. Bxe5 Rxe5 16. cxd5 Bxf1 17. Kxf1 cxd5 {We have an
interesting material imbalance here. White's two pieces are generally stronger
than a rook in a static type of position such as this one (especially
considering the doubled pawns). White can, therefore, exert some pressure in
this endgame although Black should not have problems keeping the balance with
correct play.}) 9... O-O-O 10. b3 f6 11. Bb2 fxe5 12. O-O-O Nf6 13. Qxe5 Qxe5
14. Bxe5 Ng4 $132 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7] Black has enough counterplay, though
White's structural advantage can be a long-term asset in this type of endgame.}
) 9. Nc3 Ba6 {[%csl Rc4]} 10. b3 {[%csl Ra6,Rb6] Now Black has two potentially
badly placed minor pieces on the queenside. In most cases, it is possible to
compensate for that with dynamic play in the middlegame. However, if the game
transitions into the endgame, White can often exploit these two misplaced
pieces. Sometimes, White is even ready to sacrifice a pawn for that purpose,
as in the following line:} O-O-O 11. Bb2 Re8 12. f4 f6 13. O-O-O fxe5 14. fxe5
Qxe5 15. Qxe5 Rxe5 {[%csl Ra6,Ra7,Rb6,Rc6,Rc7] and here it is possible to
obtain the initiative in the endgame thanks to the better piece coordination.
Black usually needs to spend a lot of time regrouping his queenside pieces
toward the centre.} *

