{[#] In this game, I had a very unpleasant experience as Black in the endgame.
Since I played a much lower-rated opponent, I wanted to play for a win even as
I understood that my position is worse.} 18... Qa3 19. Bc1 Qb4+ 20. Bd2 Qa3 21.
Bc1 Qc5 $2 {Trading queens is a completely wrong decision here. I thought that
I had to keep playing on but the endgame will be terrible for Black.} ({
Objectively speaking, it was best to force a draw by move repetition with} 
21... Qb4+ 22. Bd2 Qa3 $11) 22. O-O Re8 23. Bd3 Qxe3+ 24. Bxe3 $16 {[%csl Rb6,
Rb7,Ye5] White has developed fully and has a large advantage thanks to the
superior structure and much better pieces.} Ba3 25. Bd4 $1 {[%csl Ra3,Rb6,Rb7,
Ge5,Gf7,Gg6,Rg7] After this simple move, it becomes clear that Black will not
have any counterplay against the e5-pawn. At this point, I realized that
things might go south very quickly, so I played} c5 {and offered a draw. To my
terror, my opponent quickly declined it and played} 26. Bc3 g5 $2 {[%csl Rh6] 
[#] An oversight, but it was difficult to come up with anything else.} ({
It was better to play} 26... Bb4 27. Bb2 a4 28. Rad1 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Rb6,Rb7,
Rg7,Rh6][%cal Yf3h4] but anyway I did not see how I could defend against
White's plan to attack my kingside with Nh4-g6/Bg6, Rf7, etc.}) 27. h3 $6 {
White misses a tactic that would secure him a decisive advantage. The worst
thing, though, is that he keeps excellent winning chances even with simple
moves like this one.} (27. e6 Rhf8 28. Bg6 $1 ({I had hoped for} 28. exd7+ Nxd7
{[%csl Gd7]} 29. Bxa5 Re3 $132) (28. Bg7 Rg8 29. exd7+ Nxd7 30. Bxh6 Re6) 28...
Rxe6 29. Nxg5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc8]}) 27... Rhf8 28. Nh2 {[%csl Rh6][%cal Gh2g4]
As noted before, White doesn't even have to play the best moves to win the
game - that's how bad black position is.} (28. Bg6 $142 {was even stronger} Rd8
(28... Re6 29. Nxg5 $18) 29. Bxa5 Bxf3 30. Rxf3 Rxf3 31. gxf3 Bb4 32. Bxb4 cxb4
33. Kf2 $18) 28... Bb4 29. Bb2 a4 30. Rxf8 Rxf8 31. Rf1 $1 Rxf1+ 32. Kxf1 {
[%csl Rb4,Rb6,Rg5,Rh6] White exchanged both pairs of rooks which makes sense
since all of my remaining pieces are still on the queenside. My h- and g-pawns
are in peril.} Bd2 $138 ({Now, or a couple of move later, it would have been
principled to seek some counterplay with} 32... d5 {even though this would
hardly help me save the game, anyway.} 33. e6 (33. exd6 cxd6 34. Ng4 axb3 35.
axb3 h5 36. Nf6 d5 37. Nxh5 dxc4 38. bxc4 Ba6 39. Bf6 Bxc4 40. Bxc4 Nxc4 41.
Bxg5 $18) 33... axb3 34. axb3 dxc4 35. bxc4 Ba6 36. Kf2 Bxc4 37. Bf5 $1 Kb7 38.
e7 Bf7 39. Ng4 $18) 33. Bg6 (33. Ng4 $142 h5 34. Nf6 h4 35. Be4 $18 {[%csl Rg5]
was simpler.}) 33... axb3 34. axb3 Bf4 $2 {Played in time trouble with a wrong
idea in mind.} ({This was the last opportunity to play the necessary} 34... d5
{and make White work for the full point.} 35. Nf3 (35. exd6 cxd6 36. Nf3 Bf4
37. Bg7 d5 38. cxd5 g4 39. hxg4 Bxd5 $16) 35... Bf4 36. e6 dxc4 37. e7 {
I was worried about this variation but apparently Black can defend with} Bc6
38. Ne5 Bxe5 39. Bxe5 cxb3 40. e8=Q+ Bxe8 41. Bxe8 Nc4 $1 42. Bg7 b2 43. Bg6
b1=Q+ 44. Bxb1 Nd2+ 45. Ke2 Nxb1 46. g4 $1 (46. Bxh6 g4 $11) 46... Kd7 47. Bxh6
Nc3+ 48. Kf3 $16) 35. Ng4 h5 (35... d5 $142) 36. Bxh5 Be4 {[%csl Rb3][%cal
Ge4c2] This was my intended counterplay but it gets refuted easily} 37. Nf2 Bc2
38. Bd1 $18 {White is up a healthy pawn and technically winning.} Bg6 39. Bg4
Bc2 40. Bd1 Bg6 41. Be2 $4 {Unbelievable luck for me. My opponent allowed a
threefold repetition and I did not miss the chance to claim a draw.} ({He wins
easily after} 41. Ke2 d5 42. exd6 cxd6 43. Nd3 $18 {etc.}) 41... Bc2 42. Bd1
1/2-1/2

