{[#] In the previous two games, Black's decisions to trade queens were, if not
completely forced, then at least somewhat necessary in a practical sense. Here,
however, Karpov's} 16... Qf4 $6 {[%csl Ra6,Rb6] was a completely voluntary
decision and obviously not the best one considering the usual problems that
Black faces in such endgames.} ({It would have been better to keep the queens
on and look for counter-chances in the middlegame after} 16... Bf4 17. Qc2 d6 {
[%csl Ra6,Rb6][%cal Yc6c5,Ya6b7,Yb6d7] preparing to recentralize LSB and the
knight. Black would be doing okay after} 18. Nd2 (18. c5 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 dxc5 20.
Qa6+ Kb8) (18. Nc3 Nd7) 18... c5 19. Rae1 Bb7 $13 {[%csl Yb6,Yb7][%cal Gb6d7]})
17. g3 Qxd2 18. Nxd2 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Rb6,Yf6,Rh7][%cal Gd2e4,Ge4f6] White does
not have his pawns on e5 or c5 which makes black position more manageable
compared to the previous two examples. Nevertheless, white position is easier
to play since Black will need to spend a couple of tempi improving his
misplaced pieces while White can focus on targeting vulnerable pawns on the
kingside.} Rgf8 {[#]} 19. a4 {[%csl Rb3,Rb6][%cal Ga4a5] An interesting
attempt to play against b6-knight, but not the best move in the position. It
also weakens the b3-pawn in the long run.} (19. Rfd1 $1 Bb4 (19... Nd5 20. Ne4
$18 {[%cal Gd1d3]}) 20. a3 Bxd2 21. Rxd2 $14) 19... Nd5 20. Rad1 Nb4 21. Bb1 {
[%csl Ra6,Gb1,Gb2,Rb4,Rg6,Rh7] Morozevich's idea was to place his bishops on
two adjacent long diagonals in order to target black kingside more effectively.
} Be7 ({The downside of White's plan was that it leaves e2-square undefended,
but for some reason, Karpov did not take advantage of this by playing} 21...
Re2 $1 $132 {[%csl Rb1]}) 22. Rfe1 c5 {[#] Karpov is planning not only to
bring his bishop to the h1-a8 diagonal but also to reroute his knight to d4
via c6. Morozevich's response} 23. Re3 {is fairly straightforward, but not the
best.} ({It was more important to cover the d4-square first, so} 23. f4 $1 {
[%csl Yd4][%cal Gd2f3]} Bb7 24. h4 Nc6 25. Nf3 $16 {[%csl Yd4,Rh7][%cal Gh4h5]
would have kept White in the driver's seat.}) (23. Ne4 Nc6 $132) 23... Bd8 24.
Ne4 {[%csl Ge4]} d6 25. Rde1 {[%cal Ge4d6]} Re6 26. h4 $1 {[%csl Yb1,Yb2,Rg6,
Rh7][%cal Ge4g5] Naturally, White is getting ready to attack the vulnerable
kingside pawns. However, Karpov is just in time with counterplay:} Nc6 $1 {
[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc6d4]} 27. Ng5 Rxe3 28. Rxe3 Bxg5 29. hxg5 {[%csl Rh7]} Kd7 $1
{[%csl Rb3][%cal Gf8b8,Gc6d4]} 30. Be4 Nd4 31. Bd5 c6 32. Bg2 Rb8 $132 {
[%csl Rb3] Black managed to attack White's only weakness and the endgame
becomes balanced. Here we can see the strategic risk of playing a2-a4 in these
positions. If the pawn had remained on a2, White would keep a clear advantage
in this endgame.} 33. Bh3+ Kd8 34. Bf1 $5 Bc8 (34... Nxb3 35. Bf6+ {[%csl Yf6]}
Kc7 36. Re7+) 35. Rd3 Kc7 $6 (35... a5 36. Bxd4 cxd4 37. Rxd4 Rxb3 38. Rxd6+
Kc7 39. Rf6 Rb4 $132) 36. Bxd4 cxd4 37. Rxd4 Rxb3 38. Rh4 Bf5 39. g4 Bc2 40.
Rxh7+ Kb6 41. a5+ Kxa5 42. Rxa7+ Kb4 $2 {[#] A mutual oversight.} (42... Kb6
43. Rf7 $14) 43. Rc7 $2 (43. Rb7+ Kc3 (43... Kc5 44. Rxb3 Bxb3 45. Bd3) 44. Rd7
$1 $18) 43... Kc5 44. Bg2 Rb6 45. f4 Kxc4 46. Bxc6 Kd4 $14 {White is up a pawn,
but Black compensates this with his active pieces, so draw is the most likely
result. Nevertheless, Morozevich managed to squeeze out a win deep in the
endgame.} 47. Bg2 Rb2 48. Re7 d5 49. Re2 Rb1+ 50. Kf2 Bd3 51. Re6 Rb3 52. Re1
Bc2 53. Re2 Bd3 54. Ra2 Rb8 55. Ra4+ Bc4 56. Ra3 Rb2+ 57. Kg3 Re2 58. Ra7 Re3+
59. Kh4 Re2 60. Bh3 Re4 61. f5 gxf5 62. g6 Ke3 63. Ra3+ Kd2 64. g7 d4 65. Ra4
Bb3 66. Rb4 fxg4 67. Bg2 Re7 68. Rxd4+ Ke3 69. Rxg4 Bg8 70. Kh5 Re5+ 71. Kg6
Re8 72. Kf6 Kd3 73. Rg3+ Kd4 74. Bh3 Kc5 75. Bf5 Re1 76. Rc3+ Kd6 77. Rd3+ Kc5
78. Rd8 Bb3 79. Rf8 Rf1 80. Rc8+ Kd6 81. Rb8 Ba2 82. Rb6+ Kc5 83. Rb2 Bg8 84.
Rb1 Rf2 85. Re1 Bb3 86. Ke5 Rg2 87. Rc1+ Kb4 88. Kf6 Bg8 89. Rc8 Bd5 90. Bg6
Rg1 91. Rc7 Rf1+ 92. Ke5 Ba2 93. Be4 Rg1 94. Kd4 Kb5 95. Rb7+ Ka6 96. Ke5 Re1
97. Rb4 Ka5 98. Rb8 Bf7 99. Kf6 Rf1+ 100. Ke7 Bc4 101. Bg6 Rg1 102. Kf6 Ka6
103. Rb4 Rf1+ 104. Bf5 Bg8 105. Rb1 Rf2 106. Ke5 Rg2 107. Bd3+ Ka5 108. Rb5+
Ka4 109. Kf6 Rg3 110. Rb8 Rf3+ 111. Ke5 1-0

