{[%evp 0,79,19,12,12,12,6,0,0,0,0,0,0,-7,0,0,7,12,0,6,1,0,46,18,2,-9,-21,-16,
-17,0,35,12,-4,17,4,-12,-5,-5,1,1,-13,-13,-5,-35,-1,0,0,4,38,46,46,38,31,31,31,
31,53,47,40,44,59,56,54,43,70,64,77,44,61,41,37,41,35,29,47,47,89,4,26,53,221,
224]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 exd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nxc6 bxc6 6. e5 Qe7 7. Qe2
Nd5 8. c4 Ba6 9. Nd2 g6 {Kramnik plays a more complex variation than the one
examined in the previous game. Nevertheless, Caruana finds a way to force the
endgame.} 10. Nf3 Bg7 11. Bg5 f6 {This move took me by surprise, although I
must admit it's a very logical one.} ({I had looked at the following forced
variation:} 11... Qb4+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Bxd2 Nb6 14. b3 d6 15. O-O-O dxe5 16.
Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Re1 Nd7 18. f4 f6 19. fxe5 Nxe5 20. Bc3 O-O 21. Be2 Rfe8 22. Bxe5
fxe5 23. Bf3 {, with a pleasant advantage, despite the pawn deficit.}) 12. exf6
Qxe2+ 13. Bxe2 Nxf6 {[%csl Yf6]} 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Be3 {[%csl Ra7]} Rde8 {
[%csl Re2][%cal Gf6d5,Gf6g4] [#]} 16. Bd3 $1 {Caruana finds a strong and
accurate move. The key is to remove the bishop from two pins so that Black
doesn't get counterplay with ...Nd5/...Ng4.} (16. Rhe1 {is worse because of} d6
17. c5 Bxe2 18. Rxe2 Nd5 $11) 16... d6 {[%cal Yc6c5]} ({After} 16... Ng4 $2 {
White can grab the pawn safely:} 17. Bxa7 Kb7 18. h3 {, with a clear advantage.
}) 17. c5 {[%csl Rc6,Rd6] The only logical way to proceed, as otherwise, Black
would play ...c5 himself, with a comfortable position.} Bxd3 18. Rxd3 Nd5 {
The most natural move, but perhaps not the best.} (18... d5 19. Bd4 $14 {
[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7] leaves Black's position a bit awkward.}) ({However, the
accurate} 18... Ne4 $1 19. cxd6 cxd6 {would have resulted in dead equality
since White can't capture on a7 anymore due to ...c5.} 20. Bxa7 c5 {[%csl Rf2]}
) 19. cxd6 cxd6 20. Bxa7 {Black should have enough compensation here, but over
the board, it isn't so simple to prove it. Every one of Kramnik's next moves
is quite natural and hard to criticize, but each move slightly deteriorates
Black's position, until he no longer has any compensation for the pawn.} Kc7
$44 {[%csl Gd5,Yg7]} 21. Be3 Ra8 {Another small step in the wrong direction.} (
21... Rb8 22. Rd2 Rhe8 23. Re1 Nxe3 $1 {It seems difficult to part with such a
beautiful knight, but as is well known, the pieces that remain on the board
are more important than the pieces that are traded off. This exchange ensures
a bright future for Black's bishop, which is much more versatile than White's
knight. After} 24. fxe3 Rb4 {, Black has adequate compensation for the pawn.})
22. a3 Ra4 23. Re1 Rf8 $2 {After this strategic mistake Black will be
struggling for the rest of the game. It was his last chance to trade off
White's bishop.} (23... Nxe3 {is simply mandatory now.} 24. fxe3 Re8 $44 {
[%cal Gd6d5,Gc6c5] , and Black will have to suffer a bit, but he should be
able to hold the position.}) 24. Ng5 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Yg5e6,Yg5h7] Now Black
is even facing tactical problems.} Re8 (24... Kd7 25. Rb3 {threatens Rb7,
which is surprisingly difficult to counter.}) 25. Bb6+ {I was happy to trade
off some material since it became clear that my king would never be in any
danger.} Kd7 26. Rxe8 Kxe8 27. Be3 Kd7 ({Maybe Black should still try} 27...
Nxe3 28. Rxe3+ Kd7 {, although this version of the exchange is clearly
unfavourable for him.}) 28. Rb3 Kc8 29. Bd2 {[%csl Yd2]} h5 (29... h6 30. Nf7 {
wins another pawn.}) 30. Nf7 {[%csl Rd6,Rg6] I continue to pursue my advantage
in the most concrete way, but perhaps it was more practical (especially due to
my time shortage at this stage) to simply consolidate my position and begin
advancing on the queenside.} Kc7 31. Rg3 Ne7 32. b4 $1 {[%csl Ra4]} Kd7 33. Rd3
d5 34. Kc2 Nf5 35. Bc3 {A very important move, as otherwise, Black gets
sufficient counterplay with ...Nd4.} d4 (35... Rxa3 36. Bxg7 Rxd3 37. Kxd3 Nxg7
38. Ne5+ Kd6 39. Nxg6 {is most likely winning for White.}) 36. Kb3 Ra8 37. Ng5
Kd6 {[#] For the last couple of moves Kramnik has defended accurately, and it
seems like he is beginning to get counterplay with ...Kd5, supporting his
advanced d-pawn.} 38. f3 $6 {[%cal Gg5e4] An inaccuracy which.....wins the
game immediately! Surprisingly, this move, which was made with only seconds on
the clock, almost spoils all the hard work I had done.} ({The precise} 38. Kc4
$1 Rxa3 39. Bxd4 Rxd3 40. Bc5+ $1 Ke5 41. Kxd3 {gives White good chances to
score the full point, although there is still plenty of work to be done.})
38... Kd5 39. Ne4 {[#]} Ne3 $4 {A bizarre blunder, ending the game immediately.
Instead, Black had a miraculous chance to turn the game around.} (39... Rxa3+
$3 {is a move I hadn't even noticed during the game.} 40. Kxa3 Kc4 41. Rd1 (41.
Bxd4 Kxd3 42. Bxg7 Nxg7 {is close to a draw due to Black's active king.}) 41...
dxc3 {, and it seems like Black's advanced c-pawn will secure a draw.}) 40.
Rxe3 {And now it's all over. An unfortunately abrupt finish to an interesting
game. To my great shock (and probably to many others' as well) I found myself
in clear first place going into the final round. However, I wasn't quite up to
the challenge and lost without a fight against Levon Aronian, ending up in
shared second place.} 1-0

